    {'id':"y2-t4-w4-l4",'year':"Y2",'term':"T4",     'week':4,'weekLesson':4,     'sequence':"Mastery 5",'lesson':"Lesson 2",     'focus':"adding vowel suffixes after consonant + y",     'explanation':"Consolidation: when adding -ed, -er, or -est to a word ending in consonant + y, change the y to i first (e.g. hurry → hurried; dirty → dirtier); but -ing is added without any change (e.g. hurrying). Pupils practise identifying which suffix applies each time.",     'hlWords':["hurrying", "lazier", "busiest", "carried", "dirtier", "smelliest", "worrying", "tidied", "cried", "copying"]},
    {'id':"y2-t4-w4-l5",'year':"Y2",'term':"T4",     'week':4,'weekLesson':5,     'sequence':"Mastery 6",'lesson':"Lesson 1",     'focus':"adding vowel suffixes after consonant + e",     'explanation':"When a word ends in a consonant + e, drop the final e before adding the vowel suffix -ing (e.g. move → moving, bake → baking, drive → driving). The e is removed because the suffix itself begins with a vowel.",     'hlWords':["moving", "baking", "driving", "closing", "escaping", "using", "smiling", "coming", "hoping", "riding"]},
    {'id':"y2-t4-w5-l1",'year':"Y2",'term':"T4",     'week':5,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':"Mastery 6",'lesson':"Lesson 2",     'focus':"adding vowel suffixes after consonant + e",     'explanation':"When a word ends in consonant + e, drop the e before adding the vowel suffixes -ed, -er, or -est (e.g. close → closed, closer, closest; brave → braver, bravest). The rule is the same as for -ing: the final e is always removed before a vowel suffix.",     'hlWords':["closed", "closer", "closest", "braver", "bravest", "cutest", "used", "moved", "wiser", "finest"]},
    {'id':"y2-t4-w5-l2",'year':"Y2",'term':"T4",     'week':5,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':"Mastery 7",'lesson':"Lesson 1",     'focus':"adding vowel suffixes after consonant + e",     'explanation':"Consolidation: -y can also act as a vowel suffix, so the drop-e rule applies (e.g. smoke → smoky, slime → slimy). Pupils practise all five vowel suffixes — -ed, -er, -est, -ing, and -y — recognising that the final e is always dropped before any of them.",     'hlWords':["safest", "smoky", "slimy", "braver", "noticed", "waving", "spicy", "tasty", "shiny", "icy"]},
    {'id':"y2-t4-w5-l3",'year':"Y2",'term':"T4",     'week':5,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':"Mastery 7",'lesson':"Lesson 2",     'focus':"Doubling consonants when adding suffixes",     'explanation':"When a one-syllable word ends in a single short vowel followed by a single consonant, double the final consonant before adding a vowel suffix (e.g. tap → tapping, hum → hummed, stop → stopped). Words ending in consonant + consonant do not double (e.g. jump → jumped).",     'hlWords':["tapping", "stopped", "thinnest", "patting", "flipped", "sitting", "winner", "runny", "bigger", "beginning"]},
    {'id':"y2-t4-w5-l4",'year':"Y2",'term':"T4",     'week':5,'weekLesson':4,     'sequence':"Mastery 8",'lesson':"Lesson 1",     'focus':"Doubling consonants when adding suffixes",     'explanation':"Pupils distinguish three patterns: short vowel + single consonant → double before suffix (swim → swimmer); consonant + consonant → no double (tall → tallest); long vowel + consonant → no double (bump → bumpy). Applying the rule correctly depends on identifying the final two letters of the root word.",     'hlWords':["tallest", "swimmer", "dragged", "nodding", "slippy", "bumpy", "kinder", "saddest", "bumped", "yelped"]},
    {'id':"y2-t4-w5-l5",'year':"Y2",'term':"T4",     'week':5,'weekLesson':5,     'sequence':"Mastery 8",'lesson':"Lesson 2",     'focus':"Doubling consonants when adding suffixes",     'explanation':"Consolidation using all three patterns: double the consonant only when the root ends in short vowel + single consonant (fat → fattest); do not double after a long vowel or vowel digraph + consonant (sweet → sweetest, rain → rainy, dream → dreamy, float → floated, pack → packed).",     'hlWords':["beeped", "floated", "trained", "sweetest", "fattest", "dreamy", "speaking", "rainy", "packed", "cleanest"]},
    {'id':"y2-t5-w1-l1",'year':"Y2",'term':"T5",     'week':1,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':"Sequence 11",'lesson':"Lesson 1",     'focus':"adding vowel suffixes after consonant + e",     'explanation':"Mastery lesson: pupils apply the drop-e rule independently across multiple suffixes (-ing, -ed, -er), recognising that the final e is always removed before any vowel suffix (e.g. invite → inviting, hope → hoped, write → writer). Emphasis is on fluency and self-correction.",     'hlWords':["inviting", "hiding", "hoped", "writer", "making", "baking", "timing", "driving", "smiling", "moved"]},
    {'id':"y2-t5-w1-l2",'year':"Y2",'term':"T5",     'week':1,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':"Sequence 11",'lesson':"Lesson 2",     'focus':"adding vowel suffixes after consonant + e",     'explanation':"Second mastery lesson: pupils identify the drop-e rule in a connected passage, spotting words such as flamed, bravest, coming, and tasty, then apply the rule independently in a sentence. The -y suffix is revisited alongside -ing, -ed, -er, and -est.",     'hlWords':["flamed", "bravest", "coming", "tasty", "hoping", "riding", "using", "cared", "finest", "spicy"]},
    {'id':"y2-t5-w1-l3",'year':"Y2",'term':"T5",     'week':1,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':"Sequence 11",'lesson':"Lesson 3",     'focus':"Doubling consonants when adding suffixes",     'explanation':"First mastery lesson: pupils consolidate the doubling rule for one-syllable words ending in short vowel + single consonant, applying it to -ing, -ed, -er, -est, and -y suffixes (e.g. tap → tapped/tapping, stop → stopped/stopping, win → winning, mud → muddy).",     'hlWords':["tapped", "hummed", "stopped", "tapping", "humming", "stopping", "winning", "muddy", "biggest", "sitting"]},
    {'id':"y2-t5-w1-l4",'year':"Y2",'term':"T5",     'week':1,'weekLesson':4,     'sequence':"Sequence 12",'lesson':"Lesson 1",     'focus':"Doubling consonants when adding suffixes",     'explanation':"Second mastery lesson: pupils apply all three patterns — double for short vowel + single consonant (win → winner), no double for consonant + consonant (strong → strongest), no double for long vowel + consonant (treat → treated) — identifying the correct pattern before adding the suffix.",     'hlWords':["softer", "thicker", "stronger", "softest", "thickest", "strongest", "frothy", "winner", "treated", "wagged"]},
    {'id':"y2-t5-w1-l5",'year':"Y2",'term':"T5",     'week':1,'weekLesson':5,     'sequence':"Sequence 12",'lesson':"Lesson 2",     'focus':"Adding the suffix –ful and -less",     'explanation':"The suffix -ful (always one l) means 'full of' and -less means 'without'; both attach to a root word without changing its spelling (e.g. thank → thankful/thankless, colour → colourful/colourless). Pupils explore how the two suffixes give opposite meanings to the same root word.",     'hlWords':["thankful", "thankless", "colourful", "colourless", "meaningful", "meaningless", "restless", "useful", "peaceful", "hopeful"]},
    {'id':"y2-t5-w2-l1",'year':"Y2",'term':"T5",     'week':2,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':"Sequence 12",'lesson':"Lesson 3",     'focus':"Adding the suffix –ful and -less",     'explanation':"Mastery lesson revisiting -ful (one l; 'full of') and -less (two s letters; 'without'): pupils spot misspellings and apply both suffixes to the same root words, recognising that the root spelling does not change (e.g. pain → painful/painless, waste → wasteful, wish → wishful).",     'hlWords':["painful", "painless", "wasteful", "wishful", "timeless", "restless", "wonderful", "helpful", "careful", "fearless"]},
    {'id':"y2-t5-w2-l2",'year':"Y2",'term':"T5",     'week':2,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':"Sequence 13",'lesson':"Lesson 1",     'focus':"Adding the suffix –ment & -ness",     'explanation':"The suffix -ment turns a verb into a noun without changing the root (enjoy → enjoyment, improve → improvement); -ness turns an adjective into a noun showing quality or condition, changing y to i when the adjective ends in consonant + y (e.g. happy → happiness, tired → tiredness).",     'hlWords':["happiness", "excitement", "kindness", "tiredness", "commitment", "enjoyment", "improvement", "sadness", "darkness", "movement"]},
    {'id':"y2-t5-w2-l3",'year':"Y2",'term':"T5",     'week':2,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':"Sequence 13",'lesson':"Lesson 2",     'focus':"Adding the suffix –ment, -ness & -ly",     'explanation':"Three suffixes are consolidated: -ment turns verbs into nouns (enjoy → enjoyment, pay → payment); -ness turns adjectives into nouns (kind → kindness, fair → fairness); -ly turns adjectives into adverbs (quick → quickly, careful → carefully). Consonant + y endings change y to i before -ness and -ly.",     'hlWords':["quickly", "loudly", "carefully", "steadily", "happily", "kindness", "enjoyment", "clearly", "payment", "fairness"]},
    {'id':"y2-t5-w2-l4",'year':"Y2",'term':"T5",     'week':2,'weekLesson':4,     'sequence':"Sequence 13",'lesson':"Lesson 3",     'focus':"contractions",     'explanation':"An apostrophe in a contraction replaces the missing letter(s) when two words are combined: when the second word is not, the letter o is omitted (do + not = don't); when are, the a is omitted (they + are = they're); when is, the i is omitted (he + is = he's).",     'hlWords':["they're", "he's", "doesn't", "there's", "you're", "shouldn't", "isn't", "we're", "aren't", "that's"]},
    {'id':"y2-t5-w2-l5",'year':"Y2",'term':"T5",     'week':2,'weekLesson':5,     'sequence':"Sequence 14",'lesson':"Lesson 1",     'focus':"contractions",     'explanation':"Contractions using -'ll (replacing will) and -'ve (replacing have) are formed by replacing the missing letters with an apostrophe at exactly the point of omission (e.g. we + will = we'll, you + have = you've, that + will = that'll, I + have = I've).",     'hlWords':["that'll", "you've", "it'll", "there'll", "we've", "i've", "they've", "we'll", "he'll", "she'll"]},
    {'id':"y2-t5-w3-l1",'year':"Y2",'term':"T5",     'week':3,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':"Sequence 14",'lesson':"Lesson 2",     'focus':"Adding the suffix -ful",     'explanation':"The suffix -ful, meaning 'full of,' is added to a root word without changing the root's spelling, and is always spelled with only one l — never -full.",     'hlWords':["helpful", "careful", "playful", "useful", "hopeful", "cheerful", "colourful", "thankful", "peaceful", "meaningful"]},
    {'id':"y2-t5-w3-l2",'year':"Y2",'term':"T5",     'week':3,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':"Sequence 14",'lesson':"Lesson 3",     'focus':"Adding the suffix -less",     'explanation':"The suffix -less, meaning 'without,' is added to a root word without changing its spelling, and is always spelled with two s letters at the end.",     'hlWords':["hopeless", "careless", "useless", "fearless", "homeless", "helpless", "worthless", "colourless", "thankless", "harmless"]},
    {'id':"y2-t5-w3-l3",'year':"Y2",'term':"T5",     'week':3,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':"Sequence 15",'lesson':"Lesson 1",     'focus':"Adding the suffix –ful and -less",     'explanation':"The suffixes -ful ('full of') and -less ('without') can both be added to the same root word; the root spelling stays the same, -ful has one l, and -less always ends in double s.",     'hlWords':["careful", "careless", "helpful", "helpless", "useful", "useless", "restful", "restless", "playful", "fearless"]},
    {'id':"y2-t5-w3-l4",'year':"Y2",'term':"T5",     'week':3,'weekLesson':4,     'sequence':"Sequence 15",'lesson':"Lesson 2",     'focus':"Adding the suffix -ment",     'explanation':"The suffix -ment turns a verb into a noun meaning 'the act, result, or state of an action,' and is added directly to the end of the root word without any spelling change.",     'hlWords':["movement", "improvement", "development", "agreement", "payment", "enjoyment", "treatment", "punishment", "excitement", "amusement"]},
    {'id':"y2-t5-w3-l5",'year':"Y2",'term':"T5",     'week':3,'weekLesson':5,     'sequence':"Sequence 15",'lesson':"Lesson 3",     'focus':"Adding the suffix –ment & -ness",     'explanation':"The suffix -ment turns verbs into nouns and -ness turns adjectives into nouns; when an adjective ends in a consonant + y, the y changes to i before -ness is added (e.g. happy → happiness).",     'hlWords':["enjoyment", "movement", "payment", "agreement", "improvement", "darkness", "kindness", "happiness", "illness", "sadness"]},
    {'id':"y2-t5-w4-l1",'year':"Y2",'term':"T5",     'week':4,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':"Mastery 9",'lesson':"Lesson 1",     'focus':"Adding the suffix –ment, -ness & -ly",     'explanation':"Three suffixes — -ment (verb to noun), -ness (adjective to noun), and -ly (adjective to adverb) — attach to root words; if the root ends in consonant + y, the y changes to i before -ness or -ly.",     'hlWords':["quickly", "loudly", "carefully", "poorly", "clearly", "busily", "kindness", "darkness", "enjoyment", "movement"]},
    {'id':"y2-t5-w4-l2",'year':"Y2",'term':"T5",     'week':4,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':"Mastery 9",'lesson':"Lesson 2",     'focus':"Contractions",     'explanation':"A contraction joins two words into one, using an apostrophe to mark the missing letter or letters; the apostrophe sits exactly where the omitted letters were (e.g. did + not = didn't, they + are = they're).",     'hlWords':["they're", "she's", "didn't", "shouldn't", "hadn't", "you're", "it's", "there's", "don't", "can't"]},
    {'id':"y2-t5-w4-l3",'year':"Y2",'term':"T5",     'week':4,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':"Mastery 10",'lesson':"Lesson 1",     'focus':"Contractions",     'explanation':"This lesson focuses on contractions formed with 'have' and 'will' — the apostrophe replaces the missing letters in combinations such as we + have = we've and he + will = he'll.",     'hlWords':["we've", "he'll", "you've", "we're", "they'll", "that'll", "she'll", "you'll", "it's", "didn't"]},
    {'id':"y2-t5-w4-l4",'year':"Y2",'term':"T5",     'week':4,'weekLesson':4,     'sequence':"Mastery 10",'lesson':"Lesson 2",     'focus':"Contractions",     'explanation':"Pupils practise converting full phrases into contractions by identifying the omitted letters and placing the apostrophe accurately, including less common forms such as could've where have is reduced.",     'hlWords':["they're", "we'll", "it's", "isn't", "could've", "don't", "can't", "she's", "he'll", "we've"]},
    {'id':"y2-t5-w4-l5",'year':"Y2",'term':"T5",     'week':4,'weekLesson':5,     'sequence':"Mastery 11",'lesson':"Lesson 1",     'focus':"Possessive singular apostrophe",     'explanation':"When something belongs to a single owner, an apostrophe followed by s is placed directly after the owner's name; the apostrophe always comes before the s to show singular possession.",     'hlWords':["cat's", "dog's", "teacher's", "doctor's", "tree's", "bird's", "child's", "mum's", "girl's", "boy's"]},
    {'id':"y2-t5-w5-l1",'year':"Y2",'term':"T5",     'week':5,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':"Mastery 11",'lesson':"Lesson 2",     'focus':"Possessive singular apostrophe",     'explanation':"An apostrophe + s is added after a singular noun to show ownership; this applies whether the owner is a person, animal, or object — for example, the phone's screen or the city's streets.",     'hlWords':["phone's", "group's", "city's", "queen's", "lion's", "school's", "friend's", "baby's", "rabbit's", "sun's"]},
    {'id':"y2-t5-w5-l2",'year':"Y2",'term':"T5",     'week':5,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':"Mastery 12",'lesson':"Lesson 1",     'focus':"Possessive singular apostrophe",     'explanation':"This lesson consolidates the possessive apostrophe rule using longer, less familiar nouns so that pupils apply the apostrophe + s pattern confidently across a wider range of single owners.",     'hlWords':["author's", "editor's", "gardener's", "neighbour's", "baker's", "farmer's", "singer's", "dancer's", "painter's", "driver's"]},
    {'id':"y2-t5-w5-l3",'year':"Y2",'term':"T5",     'week':5,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':"Mastery 12",'lesson':"Lesson 2",     'focus':"Words ending -tion",     'explanation':"Adding -tion to a verb creates a noun meaning 'the act or result' of that action; if the verb ends in t, simply add -ion; if it ends in te, drop the e then add -ion.",     'hlWords':["action", "invention", "direction", "selection", "protection", "question", "option", "section", "fiction", "station"]},
    {'id':"y2-t5-w5-l4",'year':"Y2",'term':"T5",     'week':5,'weekLesson':4,     'sequence':"Mastery 13",'lesson':"Lesson 1",     'focus':"Words ending -tion",     'explanation':"When a verb ends in -ate, drop the -ate and add -ation to form a noun; pupils practise recognising this pattern across verbs such as locate → location and decorate → decoration.",     'hlWords':["location", "completion", "operation", "decoration", "celebration", "education", "donation", "migration", "population", "nation"]},
    {'id':"y2-t5-w5-l5",'year':"Y2",'term':"T5",     'week':5,'weekLesson':5,     'sequence':"Mastery 13",'lesson':"Lesson 2",     'focus':"Words ending -tion",     'explanation':"Pupils identify which verbs can take -tion and apply the correct form; the lesson highlights that not every word ending in a vowel + consonant can simply have -tion added, requiring careful analysis.",     'hlWords':["education", "migration", "population", "donation", "operation", "invitation", "station", "fiction", "section", "question"]},
    {'id':"y2-t6-w1-l1",'year':"Y2",'term':"T6",     'week':1,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':"Sequence 16",'lesson':"Lesson 1",     'focus':"Possessive singular apostrophe",     'explanation':"This mastery lesson revisits the rule that a singular owner takes apostrophe + s, giving pupils further practice across a varied set of nouns to secure confident, automatic use of the pattern.",     'hlWords':["sunflower's", "dog's", "baby's", "cat's", "owner's", "teacher's", "rabbit's", "hedgehog's", "butterfly's", "spider's"]},
    {'id':"y2-t6-w1-l2",'year':"Y2",'term':"T6",     'week':1,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':"Sequence 16",'lesson':"Lesson 2",     'focus':"Possessive singular apostrophe",     'explanation':"Pupils apply the possessive apostrophe within short passage contexts, identifying the single owner in each sentence and confirming the apostrophe always appears before the s.",     'hlWords':["school's", "son's", "teacher's", "pupil's", "brother's", "sister's", "parent's", "family's", "friend's", "garden's"]},
    {'id':"y2-t6-w1-l3",'year':"Y2",'term':"T6",     'week':1,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':"Sequence 16",'lesson':"Lesson 3",     'focus':"Words ending -tion",     'explanation':"This mastery lesson revisits -tion nouns formed from verbs ending in t or te, reinforcing that -tion makes the verb into a noun and noting that the suffix always sounds like 'shun' regardless of spelling.",     'hlWords':["action", "invention", "direction", "selection", "connection", "question", "section", "protection", "fiction", "station"]},
    {'id':"y2-t6-w1-l4",'year':"Y2",'term':"T6",     'week':1,'weekLesson':4,     'sequence':"Sequence 17",'lesson':"Lesson 1",     'focus':"Words ending -tion",     'explanation':"This mastery lesson focuses on the -ate → -ation pattern, where verbs ending in -ate drop those letters and add -ation to form nouns, as in educate → education and celebrate → celebration.",     'hlWords':["education", "donation", "operation", "location", "decoration", "celebration", "migration", "population", "invitation", "nation"]},
    {'id':"y2-t6-w1-l5",'year':"Y2",'term':"T6",     'week':1,'weekLesson':5,     'sequence':"Sequence 17",'lesson':"Lesson 2",     'focus':"Homophones",     'explanation':"Homophones sound identical but have different spellings and meanings; this lesson focuses on three key sets — your/you're, there/their/they're, and to/too/two — where context and meaning determine the correct choice.",     'hlWords':["there", "their", "they're", "to", "too", "two", "your", "you're", "here", "hear"]},
    {'id':"y2-t6-w2-l1",'year':"Y2",'term':"T6",     'week':2,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':"Sequence 17",'lesson':"Lesson 3",     'focus':"homophones",     'explanation':"Homophones are words that sound identical but have different spellings and meanings; this lesson covers your/you're (possession vs contraction), there/their/they're (place/possession/contraction), and to/too/two (preposition/also/number).",     'hlWords':["your", "you're", "there", "their", "they're", "to", "too", "two", "your", "they're"]},
    {'id':"y2-t6-w2-l2",'year':"Y2",'term':"T6",     'week':2,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':"Sequence 18",'lesson':"Lesson 1",     'focus':"/u/ spelt o",     'explanation':"The /u/ sound is often spelled with the letter 'o' before the consonants n, m, th, and v, as in son, come, mother, and love; this pattern is irregular and must be learnt by sight.",     'hlWords':["son", "come", "money", "love", "other", "mother", "some", "front", "won", "wonder"]},
    {'id':"y2-t6-w2-l3",'year':"Y2",'term':"T6",     'week':2,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':"Sequence 18",'lesson':"Lesson 2",     'focus':"/u/ spelt o",     'explanation':"The /u/ sound spelled 'o' before n, m, th, and v extends to less obvious words like oven, cover, won, and government, where pupils may be tempted to write 'u'.",     'hlWords':["oven", "cover", "won", "government", "brother", "another", "money", "some", "front", "other"]},
    {'id':"y2-t6-w2-l4",'year':"Y2",'term':"T6",     'week':2,'weekLesson':4,     'sequence':"Sequence 18",'lesson':"Lesson 3",     'focus':"/or/ spelt 'a' or 'ar'",     'explanation':"The /or/ sound has two unusual spellings: 'a' before l or ll (walk, wall, chalk) and 'ar' after w or qu (warm, towards, quarter); neither spelling looks like the expected 'or'.",     'hlWords':["talking", "warm", "fallen", "towards", "warmest", "wall", "ball", "walk", "quarter", "chalk"]},
    {'id':"y2-t6-w2-l5",'year':"Y2",'term':"T6",     'week':2,'weekLesson':5,     'sequence':"Sequence 19",'lesson':"Lesson 1",     'focus':"/or/ spelt 'a' or 'ar'",     'explanation':"This lesson consolidates both irregular /or/ spellings: 'a' before l or ll (talked, almost, wallpaper) and 'ar' after w or qu (wart, award, warm), helping pupils distinguish them.",     'hlWords':["talked", "almost", "wallpaper", "wart", "always", "small", "call", "ward", "award", "warm"]},
    {'id':"y2-t6-w3-l1",'year':"Y2",'term':"T6",     'week':3,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':"Sequence 19",'lesson':"Lesson 2",     'focus':"/zh/ spelt s",     'explanation':"The /zh/ sound (as in the middle of 'measure') is spelled 's' in the middle of words, most commonly before the endings -ure, -ion, and -ual, as in treasure, invasion, and usual.",     'hlWords':["treasure", "pleasure", "composure", "conclusion", "invasion", "persuasion", "usual", "visual", "casually", "unusual"]},
    {'id':"y2-t6-w3-l2",'year':"Y2",'term':"T6",     'week':3,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':"Sequence 20",'lesson':"Lesson 1",     'focus':"/er/ spelt or after w",     'explanation':"When 'w' comes before the digraph 'or', the combination makes an /er/ sound rather than /or/, giving words like word, work, worm, worth, and world their unexpected pronunciation.",     'hlWords':["word", "work", "worm", "worth", "world", "worst", "worthy", "working", "worse", "worthwhile"]},
    {'id':"y2-t6-w3-l3",'year':"Y2",'term':"T6",     'week':3,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':"Mastery 14",'lesson':"Lesson 1",     'focus':"/er/ spelt or after w",     'explanation':"This consolidation lesson extends the w+or=/er/ pattern to further words and compound forms such as worthless, worms, worded, and sword, reinforcing that 'w' changes how 'or' is pronounced.",     'hlWords':["worthless", "worse", "worms", "worded", "sword", "workers", "worldwide", "word", "work", "world"]},
    {'id':"y2-t6-w3-l4",'year':"Y2",'term':"T6",     'week':3,'weekLesson':4,     'sequence':"Mastery 14",'lesson':"Lesson 2",     'focus':"homophones",     'explanation':"The homophones your and you're sound identical but differ in meaning and spelling: your shows possession (your book), while you're is a contraction of 'you are' (you're trying hard).",     'hlWords':["your", "you're", "your", "you're", "there", "their", "they're", "to", "too", "two"]},
    {'id':"y2-t6-w3-l5",'year':"Y2",'term':"T6",     'week':3,'weekLesson':5,     'sequence':"Mastery 15",'lesson':"Lesson 1",     'focus':"homophones",     'explanation':"The homophones there (indicating a place), their (showing possession), and they're (contraction of 'they are') all sound the same but have distinct spellings and entirely different grammatical uses.",     'hlWords':["there", "their", "they're", "there", "their", "they're", "your", "you're", "to", "too"]},
    {'id':"y2-t6-w4-l1",'year':"Y2",'term':"T6",     'week':4,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':"Mastery 15",'lesson':"Lesson 2",     'focus':"homophones",     'explanation':"The homophones to (preposition or infinitive marker), too (meaning 'also' or 'excessively'), and two (the number 2) all sound the same but are spelled differently and serve different grammatical roles.",     'hlWords':["to", "too", "two", "to", "too", "two", "your", "you're", "there", "their"]},
    {'id':"y2-t6-w4-l2",'year':"Y2",'term':"T6",     'week':4,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':"Mastery 16",'lesson':"Lesson 1",     'focus':"/u/ spelt o",     'explanation':"The /u/ sound spelled 'o' before n, m, th, and v is revisited here with words like won, brother, front, and wonder, helping pupils recognise this counterintuitive spelling pattern.",     'hlWords':["won", "brother", "front", "son", "come", "money", "wonder", "nothing", "love", "other"]},
    {'id':"y2-t6-w4-l3",'year':"Y2",'term':"T6",     'week':4,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':"Mastery 16",'lesson':"Lesson 2",     'focus':"/u/ spelt o",     'explanation':"Pupils practise the /u/ spelled 'o' pattern with further words including mother, love, month, and another, reinforcing that 'o' before n, m, th, and v commonly makes the /u/ sound.",     'hlWords':["mother", "love", "month", "another", "brother", "son", "money", "some", "front", "other"]},
    {'id':"y2-t6-w4-l4",'year':"Y2",'term':"T6",     'week':4,'weekLesson':4,     'sequence':"Mastery 17",'lesson':"Lesson 1",     'focus':"/u/ spelt o",     'explanation':"This lesson extends the /u/ spelled 'o' pattern to less common words such as stomach, glove, shovel, honey, and Monday, where the unusual vowel spelling is harder to predict.",     'hlWords':["stomach", "nothing", "glove", "shovel", "honey", "monday", "cover", "wonder", "son", "monkey"]},
    {'id':"y2-t6-w4-l5",'year':"Y2",'term':"T6",     'week':4,'weekLesson':5,     'sequence':"Mastery 17",'lesson':"Lesson 2",     'focus':"/or/ spelt a before l and ll",     'explanation':"The /or/ sound is spelled 'a' before l or ll in common words such as walk, talk, chalk, ball, hall, and wall; the letter 'l' alters the vowel sound to produce /or/.",     'hlWords':["walk", "talk", "chalk", "always", "ball", "hallway", "smallest", "wall", "hall", "call"]},
    {'id':"y2-t6-w5-l1",'year':"Y2",'term':"T6",     'week':5,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':"Mastery 18",'lesson':"Lesson 1",     'focus':"/or/ spelt ar",     'explanation':"The /or/ sound is spelled 'ar' after w or qu in words like warm, ward, quarter, and towards; pupils must learn that 'w' and 'qu' change the expected /ar/ sound to /or/.",     'hlWords':["warm", "warship", "towards", "quarter", "ward", "award", "warmest", "quartz", "swarm", "rewarded"]},
    {'id':"y2-t6-w5-l2",'year':"Y2",'term':"T6",     'week':5,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':"Mastery 18",'lesson':"Lesson 2",     'focus':"/or/ spelt a and ar",     'explanation':"This consolidation lesson practises both /or/ spellings together: 'ar' after w or qu (wardrobe, awards, swarm, quarter) and 'a' before l or ll (talking, fallen, wall, always).",     'hlWords':["wardrobe", "awards", "talking", "fallen", "quarter", "warm", "wall", "ball", "swarm", "always"]},
    {'id':"y2-t6-w5-l3",'year':"Y2",'term':"T6",     'week':5,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':"Mastery 19",'lesson':"Lesson 1",     'focus':"/er/ spelt or after w",     'explanation':"When 'w' precedes 'or', the digraph makes an /er/ sound; this introductory lesson helps pupils recognise the pattern in core words: worse, worst, worthy, worship, word, work, and world.",     'hlWords':["worse", "worst", "worthy", "worship", "word", "worker", "worth", "world", "worm", "workbook"]},
    {'id':"y2-t6-w5-l4",'year':"Y2",'term':"T6",     'week':5,'weekLesson':4,     'sequence':"Mastery 20",'lesson':"Lesson 1",     'focus':"/er/ spelt or after w",     'explanation':"This lesson consolidates the w+or=/er/ pattern, extending practice to compound words such as bookworm and keyworker, and asking pupils to identify words where 'or' after 'w' does not follow the rule.",     'hlWords':["worst", "bookworm", "keyworker", "worship", "worthless", "word", "work", "world", "worm", "worse"]},
    {'id':"y2-t6-w5-l5",'year':"Y2",'term':"T6",     'week':5,'weekLesson':5,     'sequence':"Mastery 20",'lesson':"Lesson 2",     'focus':"/zh/ spelt s",     'explanation':"The /zh/ sound is spelled 's' between vowels, most reliably before the endings -ure, -ion, and -ual, as in leisure, explosion, and casual; this pattern appears in longer, Latinate words.",     'hlWords':["leisure", "pleasure", "composure", "version", "explosion", "persuasion", "casual", "visually", "unusual", "closure"]},
    {'id':"y3-t1-w1-l1",'year':"Y3",'term':"T1",     'week':1,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':"Revisit",'lesson':"Lesson 1",     'focus':"words ending -le/-el/-al/-il",     'explanation':"The -le ending is the most common and usually follows a consonant. The -el ending follows m, n, r, s, v, or w (e.g. tunnel, squirrel, travel). This lesson revisits -le and -el words so pupils can sort and apply the correct ending by checking the letter before it.",     'hlWords':["paddle", "tunnel", "squirrel", "jingle", "swivel", "uncle", "stable", "camel", "puzzle", "puddle"]},
    {'id':"y3-t1-w1-l2",'year':"Y3",'term':"T1",     'week':1,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':"Revisit",'lesson':"Lesson 2",     'focus':"words ending -le/-el/-al/-il",     'explanation':"The -al ending is often used when the word is an adjective, such as magical from magic. This lesson focuses on -al adjectives alongside -le and -el words, helping pupils recognise that the word class can be a clue to which unstressed ending to apply.",     'hlWords':["national", "example", "shovel", "novel", "royal", "humble", "magical", "tickle", "vessel", "personal"]},
    {'id':"y3-t1-w1-l3",'year':"Y3",'term':"T1",     'week':1,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':"Revisit",'lesson':"Lesson 3",     'focus':"words ending -le/-el/-al/-il",     'explanation':"There is no consistent rule for the -il ending; pupils must learn these words by heart. This lesson consolidates all four endings by spotlighting the -il group (e.g. pencil, fossil, pupil, nostril) so pupils can distinguish them from the more common -le and -el patterns.",     'hlWords':["evil", "pupil", "pencil", "civil", "fossil", "council", "nostril", "stencil", "until", "basil"]},
    {'id':"y3-t1-w2-l1",'year':"Y3",'term':"T1",     'week':2,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':"Revisit",'lesson':"Lesson 4",     'focus':"adding -es after y",     'explanation':"When a noun or verb ends in consonant + y, change the y to i before adding -es (e.g. party → parties, carry → carries). When it ends in vowel + y, simply add s (e.g. chimney → chimneys). This lesson introduces the rule through sorting and patterning activities.",     'hlWords':["pennies", "cities", "libraries", "enemies", "countries", "parties", "chimneys", "bodies", "families", "copies"]},
    {'id':"y3-t1-w2-l2",'year':"Y3",'term':"T1",     'week':2,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':"Revisit",'lesson':"Lesson 5",     'focus':"adding -es after y",     'explanation':"Pupils consolidate the consonant + y → -ies rule by spotting errors and applying the rule to a range of nouns and verbs. Vowel + y words (e.g. holidays, chimneys) are contrasted to reinforce that only the consonant + y pattern triggers the y → i change before -es.",     'hlWords':["stories", "parties", "babies", "puppies", "holidays", "copies", "lorries", "valleys", "berries", "chimneys"]},
    {'id':"y3-t1-w2-l3",'year':"Y3",'term':"T1",     'week':2,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':"Revisit",'lesson':"Lesson 6",     'focus':"adding -es after y",     'explanation':"This final lesson in the unit asks pupils to independently apply both -ies and -s rules across a broader range of words, using tick-box tasks and sentence completion to confirm mastery of when to change y to i and when to leave the y and add only s.",     'hlWords':["families", "diaries", "delays", "runways", "countries", "puppies", "nurseries", "journeys", "daisies", "butterflies"]},
    {'id':"y3-t1-w3-l1",'year':"Y3",'term':"T1",     'week':3,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':"Revisit",'lesson':"Lesson 7",     'focus':"adding vowel suffixes",     'explanation':"When a word ends in consonant + y, add -ing without change (e.g. carrying), but change y to i before -ed (e.g. carried, terrified, married). This lesson focuses on -ing and -ed suffixes added to consonant + y verbs, practising both forms side by side.",     'hlWords':["burying", "buried", "carrying", "carried", "terrifying", "terrified", "replying", "replied", "multiplying", "married"]},
    {'id':"y3-t1-w3-l2",'year':"Y3",'term':"T1",     'week':3,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':"Revisit",'lesson':"Lesson 8",     'focus':"adding vowel suffixes",     'explanation':"When adding -er or -est to a word ending in consonant + y, change y to i before the suffix (e.g. grumpy → grumpier, grumpiest). This lesson focuses on comparative and superlative adjectives formed from consonant + y base words, contrasting -er and -est pairs.",     'hlWords':["grumpier", "grumpiest", "noisier", "noisiest", "luckier", "luckiest", "funnier", "funniest", "scarier", "scariest"]},
    {'id':"y3-t1-w3-l3",'year':"Y3",'term':"T1",     'week':3,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':"Revisit",'lesson':"Lesson 9",     'focus':"adding vowel suffixes",     'explanation':"When a word ends in a consonant + silent e, drop the e before adding a vowel suffix (e.g. smile → smiling, late → latest, breeze → breezy). This lesson focuses on the e-drop rule applied to -ed, -er, -est, -ing, and -y suffixes across a range of common words.",     'hlWords':["closer", "escaped", "smiling", "breezy", "coming", "latest", "bravest", "amazing", "racing", "shining"]},
    {'id':"y3-t1-w4-l1",'year':"Y3",'term':"T1",     'week':4,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':"Revisit",'lesson':"Lesson 10",     'focus':"doubling consonants in one-syllable words",     'explanation':"When a one-syllable word ends in a single short vowel followed by a single consonant, double the consonant before adding a vowel suffix (e.g. hot → hottest, tap → tapping, flat → flattest). If the word ends in two consonants or a long vowel, the consonant is not doubled.",     'hlWords':["hottest", "tapping", "flipper", "jammy", "planned", "thinnest", "sunny", "biggest", "dropped", "stopping"]},
    {'id':"y3-t1-w4-l2",'year':"Y3",'term':"T1",     'week':4,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':"Revisit",'lesson':"Lesson 11",     'focus':"doubling consonants in one-syllable words",     'explanation':"Pupils continue practising the short vowel + consonant doubling rule with additional suffixes (-ed, -er, -y), learning to distinguish words that double (e.g. fun → funny, hot → hotter) from those that do not because they end in two consonants (e.g. bump → bumped, sink → sinking).",     'hlWords':["sinking", "funny", "flipped", "hotter", "bumped", "flattest", "thinner", "camped", "planning", "sadder"]},
    {'id':"y3-t1-w4-l3",'year':"Y3",'term':"T1",     'week':4,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':"Revisit",'lesson':"Lesson 12",     'focus':"doubling consonants in one-syllable words",     'explanation':"This lesson extends the doubling rule to include long vowel + consonant words (e.g. dream → dreaming), which do not double, alongside short vowel + consonant words that do (e.g. drip → drippy, slip → slipped), helping pupils apply the full decision process across all three patterns.",     'hlWords':["fattest", "packed", "slipped", "scanner", "drippy", "dreaming", "beamed", "locking", "drummer", "clapping"]},
    {'id':"y3-t1-w5-l1",'year':"Y3",'term':"T1",     'week':5,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':"Revisit",'lesson':"Lesson 13",     'focus':"apostrophes",     'explanation':"Apostrophes for contraction replace the missing letter or letters when two words are joined (e.g. did + not → didn't, you + have → you've). This lesson revisits common contractions so pupils can recognise which letters are omitted and place the apostrophe accurately in the correct position.",     'hlWords':["you've", "we'll", "didn't", "they'll", "wasn't", "you're", "don't", "they've", "i'm", "can't"]},
    {'id':"y3-t1-w5-l2",'year':"Y3",'term':"T1",     'week':5,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':"Revisit",'lesson':"Lesson 14",     'focus':"apostrophes",     'explanation':"Apostrophes for possession show that something belongs to a singular owner; the apostrophe is placed before the s (e.g. the dog's bowl, the farmer's hat). This lesson focuses on identifying the owner in a sentence and correctly inserting the possessive apostrophe before the s.",     'hlWords':["dog's", "anna's", "friend's", "farmer's", "teacher's", "child's", "artist's", "sun's", "girl's", "boy's"]},
    {'id':"y3-t1-w5-l3",'year':"Y3",'term':"T1",     'week':5,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':"Revisit",'lesson':"Lesson 15",     'focus':"apostrophes",     'explanation':"Pupils consolidate possessive apostrophes through independent application, inserting missing apostrophes into sentences with singular possessors (e.g. book's pages, tree's branches, baby's toys). Contrasting different singular nouns reinforces that the apostrophe always comes before the s, regardless of the owner's identity.",     'hlWords':["book's", "tree's", "baby's", "clock's", "cat's", "flower's", "car's", "bird's", "street's", "garden's"]},
    {'id':"y3-t2-w1-l1",'year':"Y3",'term':"T2",     'week':1,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':"Sequence 2",'lesson':"Lesson 1",     'focus':"doubling consonants: identifying words ending in two consonants",     'explanation':"When a word ends in two consonants, we do not need to double anything before adding a suffix. Understanding which words end in a single consonant or two consonants helps us decide whether to double later. Words like jump, bank, and drift all end in two consonants so they follow the simple add-the-suffix rule.",     'hlWords':["jump", "bank", "drift", "stack", "blend", "strong", "first", "pencil", "spring", "crisp"]},
    {'id':"y3-t2-w1-l2",'year':"Y3",'term':"T2",     'week':1,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':"Sequence 2",'lesson':"Lesson 2",     'focus':"doubling the final consonant before vowel suffixes in single-syllable words",     'explanation':"When a single-syllable word ends in one vowel followed by one consonant, we double the final consonant before adding a vowel suffix like -ed or -ing. For example, plan becomes planned and drop becomes dropped. This rule protects the short vowel sound in the root word.",     'hlWords':["planned", "planning", "dropped", "dropping", "hummed", "humming", "patted", "patting", "running", "occurring"]},
    {'id':"y3-t2-w1-l3",'year':"Y3",'term':"T2",     'week':1,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':"Sequence 2",'lesson':"Lesson 3",     'focus':"doubling consonants: two-syllable words where the first syllable is stressed",     'explanation':"When a two-syllable word has the stress on the first syllable, we simply add the vowel suffix without doubling the consonant. For example, garden becomes gardening and enter becomes entered. Listening to where the stress falls in the word helps you decide whether doubling is needed.",     'hlWords':["limited", "limiting", "entered", "entering", "happened", "happening", "gardening", "gardener", "listened", "listening"]},
    {'id':"y3-t2-w2-l1",'year':"Y3",'term':"T2",     'week':2,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':"Sequence 2",'lesson':"Lesson 4",     'focus':"doubling consonants: two-syllable words where the second syllable is stressed",     'explanation':"When a two-syllable word ends in one vowel followed by one consonant and the stress falls on the second syllable, we double the final consonant before a vowel suffix. For example, admit becomes admitted and permit becomes permitted. When the first syllable is stressed instead, we simply add the suffix without doubling.",     'hlWords':["admitted", "admitting", "recurring", "recurred", "forgotten", "forgetting", "propelled", "permitted", "permitting", "listening"]},
    {'id':"y3-t2-w2-l2",'year':"Y3",'term':"T2",     'week':2,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':"Sequence 2",'lesson':"Lesson 5",     'focus':"doubling consonants: applying stress rules across multi-syllable words",     'explanation':"Whether to double depends on which syllable is stressed. When the second syllable is stressed and ends in vowel plus consonant, double the consonant before a vowel suffix, for example prefer becomes preferred. When the first syllable is stressed, simply add the suffix, as in offer becoming offering.",     'hlWords':["preferred", "preferring", "beginning", "regretting", "regretted", "inference", "inferring", "transmitting", "offering", "gardening"]},
    {'id':"y3-t2-w2-l3",'year':"Y3",'term':"T2",     'week':2,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':"Sequence 2",'lesson':"Lesson 6",     'focus':"consolidating rules for doubling consonants before vowel suffixes",     'explanation':"To decide whether to double, check three things: does the word end in one vowel then one consonant, is there no long vowel sound, and is the final syllable stressed? If all three apply, double the consonant. Words like infer become inferring but offer becomes offering because the stress falls on a different syllable.",     'hlWords':["inferring", "inference", "annoying", "offering", "brushing", "beginning", "preferred", "admitted", "occurring", "forgotten"]},
    {'id':"y3-t2-w3-l1",'year':"Y3",'term':"T2",     'week':3,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':"Sequence 2",'lesson':"Lesson 7",     'focus':"adding the -ly suffix to root words",     'explanation':"For most root words we simply add -ly to make an adverb, for example kind becomes kindly and certain becomes certainly. When the root word already ends in the letter l, adding -ly creates a double l, as in real becoming really. There are some exceptions to this basic rule, such as when a word ends in y or -le.",     'hlWords':["kindly", "certainly", "ideally", "monthly", "really", "completely", "friendly", "cowardly", "generally", "shortly"]},
    {'id':"y3-t2-w3-l2",'year':"Y3",'term':"T2",     'week':3,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':"Sequence 2",'lesson':"Lesson 8",     'focus':"adding -ly when the root word ends in y: change y to i",     'explanation':"When a root word ends in the letter y, you must change the y to i before adding the -ly suffix. For example, happy becomes happily and easy becomes easily. This rule applies to all root words ending in y, so checking the final letter of the root word is the key step.",     'hlWords':["guiltily", "differently", "ordinarily", "easily", "heavily", "naughtily", "importantly", "luckily", "busily", "happily"]},
    {'id':"y3-t2-w3-l3",'year':"Y3",'term':"T2",     'week':3,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':"Sequence 2",'lesson':"Lesson 9",     'focus':"adding -ly: practising the y to i rule across a range of words",     'explanation':"When adding -ly to a word ending in y, change the y to i first, so ready becomes readily and happy becomes happily. Words that do not end in y simply take -ly at the end, as in extreme becoming extremely. Checking the final letter of the root word before spelling the adverb form is the key habit to build.",     'hlWords':["readily", "happily", "joyfully", "warily", "recently", "unhappily", "angrily", "extremely", "certainly", "primarily"]},
    {'id':"y3-t2-w4-l1",'year':"Y3",'term':"T2",     'week':4,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':"Lesson 1",'lesson':"",     'focus':"adding -ly when the root word ends in -le: replace -le with -ly",     'explanation':"When a root word ends in -le, remove the -le and replace it with -ly to form the adverb, so gentle becomes gently and humble becomes humbly. If the word ends in y, change y to i; if it ends in -le, swap -le for -ly; otherwise simply add -ly to the end of the root word.",     'hlWords':["gently", "humbly", "simply", "feebly", "stably", "crumbly", "crazily", "clumsily", "particularly", "usually"]},
    {'id':"y3-t2-w4-l2",'year':"Y3",'term':"T2",     'week':4,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':"Lesson 2",'lesson':"",     'focus':"adding -ally after root words ending in -ic",     'explanation':"When we want to turn a word into an adverb using -ly, most root words just need -ly added on. But if the root word ends in -ic, we must add -ally instead of just -ly. For example, the word magic becomes magically, not magicly.",     'hlWords':["frantically", "lyrically", "genetically", "magically", "ironically", "medically", "basically", "musically", "dramatically", "famously"]},
    {'id':"y3-t2-w4-l3",'year':"Y3",'term':"T2",     'week':4,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':"Lesson 3",'lesson':"",     'focus':"applying all -ly suffix rules: adding -ly, -ily, and -ally",     'explanation':"There are four rules for adding -ly to a root word. Most root words just take -ly. If the root ends in y, change the y to i before adding -ly. If the root ends in -le, change -le to -ly. If the root ends in -ic, add -ally instead. For example, guilty becomes guiltily and frantic becomes frantically.",     'hlWords':["horribly", "certainly", "necessarily", "classically", "guiltily", "wrinkly", "frantically", "logically", "perfectly", "humbly"]},
    {'id':"y3-t2-w5-l1",'year':"Y3",'term':"T2",     'week':5,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':"Lesson 4",'lesson':"",     'focus':"adding the -ly suffix (revision and application)",     'explanation':"When we add -ly to a root word to make an adverb, we follow four key rules. Most words simply take -ly, but words ending in y change to -ily, words ending in -le change to -ly, and words ending in -ic take -ally. Practising these rules helps us spell adverbs correctly every time.",     'hlWords':["famously", "ordinarily", "crumbly", "frantically", "happily", "gently", "magically", "certainly", "busily", "strangely"]},
    {'id':"y3-t2-w5-l2",'year':"Y3",'term':"T2",     'week':5,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':"Lesson 5",'lesson':"",     'focus':"adding the -ly suffix: consolidating all four spelling rules",     'explanation':"We add -ly to root words to make adverbs, but the spelling changes depending on how the root word ends. Words ending in y change y to i; words ending in -le drop the e and keep the l; words ending in -ic add -ally. Knowing all four rules lets us add -ly to any word confidently.",     'hlWords':["strangely", "naughtily", "humbly", "musically", "peacefully", "happily", "frantically", "famously", "ordinarily", "possibly"]},
    {'id':"y3-t2-w5-l3",'year':"Y3",'term':"T2",     'week':5,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':"Lesson 6",'lesson':"",     'focus':"adding the -ly suffix: applying rules across all word endings",     'explanation':"To add -ly correctly, we check the ending of the root word first. Most words just take -ly, words ending in y become -ily, words ending in -le become -ly, and words ending in -ic take -ally. Checking the root word ending before writing helps us choose the right spelling every time.",     'hlWords':["extremely", "busily", "wrinkly", "genetically", "famously", "ordinarily", "crumbly", "frantically", "happily", "gently"]},
    {'id':"y3-t3-w1-l1",'year':"Y3",'term':"T3",     'week':1,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':"Sequence 3",'lesson':"Lesson 1",     'focus':"adding the -ous suffix to full root words",     'explanation':"The suffix -ous turns a noun or adjective into an adjective meaning full of or having that quality. For most full root words, we simply add -ous to the end without changing anything. For example, poison becomes poisonous and mountain becomes mountainous.",     'hlWords':["poisonous", "dangerous", "joyous", "hazardous", "mountainous", "prosperous", "ruinous", "glamorous", "wondrous", "numerous"]},
    {'id':"y3-t3-w1-l2",'year':"Y3",'term':"T3",     'week':1,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':"Sequence 3",'lesson':"Lesson 2",     'focus':"adding the -ous suffix: full root words and words not containing a clear root",     'explanation':"Most root words simply take the -ous suffix to form an adjective. Some -ous words, such as enormous and tremendous, do not contain a recognisable English root word. We learn to spell these by looking carefully at the word and practising it in sentences.",     'hlWords':["venomous", "hazardous", "mountainous", "horrendous", "enormous", "generous", "ominous", "tremendous", "poisonous", "dangerous"]},
    {'id':"y3-t3-w1-l3",'year':"Y3",'term':"T3",     'week':1,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':"Sequence 3",'lesson':"Lesson 3",     'focus':"adding -ous when the root word ends in a silent e",     'explanation':"When a root word ends in a silent e, we usually drop the e before adding -ous. For example, fame becomes famous and nerve becomes nervous. Some words like grievous keep a slightly different form, so it helps to look carefully at the spelling when we learn them.",     'hlWords':["famous", "nervous", "continuous", "grievous", "horrendous", "ominous", "momentous", "enormous", "courageous", "joyous"]},
    {'id':"y3-t3-w2-l1",'year':"Y3",'term':"T3",     'week':2,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':"Sequence 3",'lesson':"Lesson 4",     'focus':"adding -ous: including -eous after soft g (courageous)",     'explanation':"For most root words, we add -ous directly to make an adjective. When a root word ends in ge, such as courage, we keep the e and add -ous to make courageous, so that the g keeps its soft sound. Checking the root word ending helps us decide whether to use -ous or -eous.",     'hlWords':["enormous", "mountainous", "nervous", "courageous", "famous", "venomous", "poisonous", "hazardous", "continuous", "ominous"]},
    {'id':"y3-t3-w2-l2",'year':"Y3",'term':"T3",     'week':2,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':"Sequence 3",'lesson':"Lesson 5",     'focus':"adding -ous: including y to i changes and -eous endings",     'explanation':"When we add -ous to a root word ending in y, we change the y to i first, just as we do with -ly. For example, fury becomes furious and mystery becomes mysterious. Words ending in ge also keep the e to make -eous, such as courageous, to preserve the soft g sound.",     'hlWords':["famous", "furious", "poisonous", "courageous", "mysterious", "venomous", "mountainous", "enormous", "nervous", "joyous"]},
    {'id':"y3-t3-w2-l3",'year':"Y3",'term':"T3",     'week':2,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':"Sequence 3",'lesson':"Lesson 6",     'focus':"adding the -ous suffix",     'explanation':"When we add the suffix -ous to a root word, it turns a noun into an adjective meaning 'full of' or 'having the quality of'. If the root word ends in -e, we usually drop the e before adding -ous (outrage → outrageous). If the root word ends in -our, we drop the u before adding -ous (humour → humorous).",     'hlWords':["outrageous", "mountainous", "humorous", "victorious", "vaporous", "courageous", "famous", "continuous", "dangerous", "glorious"]},
    {'id':"y3-t3-w3-l1",'year':"Y3",'term':"T3",     'week':3,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':"Mastery 1",'lesson':"Lesson 1",     'focus':"",     'explanation':"These words test whether pupils can correctly apply the doubling rule depending on where the stress falls. Words like gardening and happened do not double because the stress is on the first syllable. Forgetting doubles because the stress falls on the final syllable.",     'hlWords':["forgetting", "beginning", "happening", "entered", "listened", "occurring", "gardening", "offering", "preferring", "happened"]},
    {'id':"y3-t3-w3-l2",'year':"Y3",'term':"T3",     'week':3,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':"Mastery 1",'lesson':"Lesson 2",     'focus':"",     'explanation':"These words test whether pupils can correctly apply the doubling rule depending on where the stress falls. Words like gardening and happened do not double because the stress is on the first syllable. Forgetting doubles because the stress falls on the final syllable.",     'hlWords':["forgetting", "beginning", "entering", "happening", "gardening", "occurring", "committing", "listened", "happened", "suffering"]},
    {'id':"y3-t3-w3-l3",'year':"Y3",'term':"T3",     'week':3,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':"Mastery 1",'lesson':"Lesson 3",     'focus':"",     'explanation':"These words test whether pupils can correctly apply the doubling rule depending on where the stress falls. Words like gardening and happened do not double because the stress is on the first syllable. Forgetting doubles because the stress falls on the final syllable.",     'hlWords':["beginning", "regretted", "visited", "inferred", "beginner", "regretting", "inference", "occurring", "preferred", "suffered"]},
    {'id':"y3-t3-w4-l1",'year':"Y3",'term':"T3",     'week':4,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':"Mastery 2",'lesson':"Lesson 1",     'focus':"in the first set, the odd one out is frantically because it is the…",     'explanation':"When adding -ly to words ending in -ic, we add -ally rather than just -ly (logic → logically, frantic → frantically, irony → ironically). The -ally ending produces the /uh-lee/ sound. This is one of several adjustments needed before adding -ly.",     'hlWords':["usually", "exactly", "likely", "lively", "cowardly", "logically", "completely", "genetically", "ironically", "musically"]},
    {'id':"y3-t3-w4-l2",'year':"Y3",'term':"T3",     'week':4,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':"Mastery 2",'lesson':"Lesson 2",     'focus':"in the first set, the odd one out is frantically because it is the…",     'explanation':"When adding -ly to words ending in -ic, we add -ally rather than just -ly (logic → logically, frantic → frantically, irony → ironically). The -ally ending produces the /uh-lee/ sound. This is one of several adjustments needed before adding -ly.",     'hlWords':["heavily", "possibly", "terribly", "angrily", "humbly", "subtly", "guiltily", "drowsily", "wrinkly", "twinkly"]},
    {'id':"y3-t3-w4-l3",'year':"Y3",'term':"T3",     'week':4,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':"Mastery 2",'lesson':"Lesson 3",     'focus':"in the first set, the odd one out is frantically because it is the…",     'explanation':"When adding -ly to words ending in -ic, we add -ally rather than just -ly (logic → logically, frantic → frantically, irony → ironically). The -ally ending produces the /uh-lee/ sound. This is one of several adjustments needed before adding -ly.",     'hlWords':["logically", "frantically", "basically", "magically", "comically", "carefully", "clearly", "heroically", "musically", "typically"]},
    {'id':"y3-t3-w5-l1",'year':"Y3",'term':"T3",     'week':5,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':"Mastery 3",'lesson':"Lesson 1",     'focus':"",     'explanation':"When we add the suffix -ous, some root words need a small change. If the root ends in e, remove it (adventure → adventurous, fame → famous). If the root ends in ge, keep the e so the g stays soft (courage → courageous, advantage → advantageous). If the root ends in our, drop the u (glamour → glamorous, humour → humorous).",     'hlWords':["famous", "dangerous", "adventurous", "gorgeous", "hazardous", "joyous", "mountainous", "continuous", "carnivorous", "advantageous"]},
    {'id':"y3-t3-w5-l2",'year':"Y3",'term':"T3",     'week':5,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':"Mastery 3",'lesson':"Lesson 2",     'focus':"",     'explanation':"When we add the suffix -ous, some root words need a small change. If the root ends in e, remove it (adventure → adventurous, fame → famous). If the root ends in ge, keep the e so the g stays soft (courage → courageous, advantage → advantageous). If the root ends in our, drop the u (glamour → glamorous, humour → humorous).",     'hlWords':["various", "furious", "generous", "victorious", "tremendous", "ominous", "harmonious", "glorious", "vaporous", "rigorous"]},
    {'id':"y3-t3-w5-l3",'year':"Y3",'term':"T3",     'week':5,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':"Mastery 3",'lesson':"Lesson 3",     'focus':"",     'explanation':"When we add the suffix -ous, some root words need a small change. If the root ends in e, remove it (adventure → adventurous, fame → famous). If the root ends in ge, keep the e so the g stays soft (courage → courageous, advantage → advantageous). If the root ends in our, drop the u (glamour → glamorous, humour → humorous).",     'hlWords':["famous", "dangerous", "adventurous", "courageous", "glamorous", "humorous", "gorgeous", "mountainous", "generous", "joyous"]},
    {'id':"y3-t4-w1-l1",'year':"Y3",'term':"T4",     'week':1,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':"Sequence 4",'lesson':"Lesson 1",     'focus':"words ending -sion (from verbs ending -se)",     'explanation':"Some nouns end in the suffix -sion, which sounds like 'zhun'. When a verb ends in -se, we can remove the -se and add -sion to make a noun (confuse → confusion, revise → revision). The -sion ending always follows this pattern when the root verb ends in -se.",     'hlWords':["version", "confusion", "revision", "fusion", "television", "decision", "invasion", "conclusion", "erosion", "explosion"]},
    {'id':"y3-t4-w1-l2",'year':"Y3",'term':"T4",     'week':1,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':"Sequence 4",'lesson':"Lesson 2",     'focus':"words ending -sion (from verbs ending -se or -de)",     'explanation':"Nouns ending in -sion are often formed from verbs ending in -se or -de. We remove the verb ending and add -sion instead (revise → revision, decide → decision). The -sion spelling gives these nouns a 'zhun' sound at the end.",     'hlWords':["version", "confusion", "revision", "fusion", "television", "decision", "invasion", "conclusion", "erosion", "diffusion"]},
    {'id':"y3-t4-w1-l3",'year':"Y3",'term':"T4",     'week':1,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':"Sequence 4",'lesson':"Lesson 3",     'focus':"words ending -sion (from verbs ending -se or -de)",     'explanation':"When a verb ends in -se or -de, we can form a noun by removing that ending and adding -sion (erode → erosion, corrode → corrosion, diffuse → diffusion). These -sion words all make a soft 'zhun' sound at the end and are always nouns.",     'hlWords':["version", "confusion", "revision", "decision", "invasion", "conclusion", "erosion", "diffusion", "corrosion", "tension"]},
    {'id':"y3-t4-w2-l1",'year':"Y3",'term':"T4",     'week':2,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':"Sequence 5",'lesson':"Lesson 1",     'focus':"homophones",     'explanation':"Homophones are words that sound exactly the same when you say them aloud but have different spellings and completely different meanings. It is important to choose the correct spelling depending on the meaning you want (for example, 'here' means in this place, while 'hear' means to listen). You must think about the meaning of the word in the sentence to get the right spelling.",     'hlWords':["here", "hear", "there", "their", "where", "wear", "right", "write", "no", "know"]},
    {'id':"y3-t4-w2-l2",'year':"Y3",'term':"T4",     'week':2,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':"Sequence 5",'lesson':"Lesson 2",     'focus':"homophones",     'explanation':"Homophones are words that sound the same but are spelled differently and have different meanings. For example, 'male' describes a boy or man, while 'mail' means letters or post. You always need to think about what the word means in the sentence before deciding which spelling to use.",     'hlWords':["male", "mail", "here", "hear", "there", "their", "where", "wear", "right", "write"]},
    {'id':"y3-t4-w2-l3",'year':"Y3",'term':"T4",     'week':2,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':"Sequence 5",'lesson':"Lesson 3",     'focus':"homophones",     'explanation':"Homophones sound identical when spoken aloud but have different spellings and meanings. For example, 'great' means wonderful or large, while 'grate' means to shred food or a metal frame. To choose the correct homophone, you must think carefully about the meaning you need in your sentence.",     'hlWords':["great", "grate", "male", "mail", "here", "hear", "there", "their", "right", "write"]},
    {'id':"y3-t4-w3-l1",'year':"Y3",'term':"T4",     'week':3,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':"Sequence 6",'lesson':"Lesson 1",     'focus':"doubling consonants before vowel suffixes in stressed final syllables",     'explanation':"When a word has more than one syllable and ends in a single short vowel followed by a single consonant, we look at which syllable is stressed. If the final syllable is the stressed one, we double the consonant before adding a vowel suffix like -ing or -ed. If the first syllable is stressed, we do not double the consonant.",     'hlWords':["forgetting", "beginning", "referring", "admitted", "regretted", "committed", "gardening", "following", "opening", "controlled"]},
    {'id':"y3-t4-w3-l2",'year':"Y3",'term':"T4",     'week':3,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':"Sequence 6",'lesson':"Lesson 2",     'focus':"doubling consonants before vowel suffixes in stressed final syllables",     'explanation':"We only double the final consonant before a vowel suffix when the root word has more than one syllable, ends in a single short vowel plus a single consonant, and the final syllable is the stressed one. If the root word ends in a long vowel sound or two consonants, we do not double. Identifying the stressed syllable is the key to getting this right.",     'hlWords':["forgotten", "forgetting", "beginning", "admitted", "regretted", "committed", "referring", "entered", "happened", "avoiding"]},
    {'id':"y3-t4-w3-l3",'year':"Y3",'term':"T4",     'week':3,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':"Sequence 6",'lesson':"Lesson 3",     'focus':"doubling consonants before vowel suffixes in stressed final syllables",     'explanation':"When the final syllable of a root word is stressed and it ends in a single short vowel plus a single consonant, we double that consonant before adding a vowel suffix (begin → beginning, regret → regretted). When the first syllable is stressed instead, we do not double the consonant (visit → visited, infer → inference).",     'hlWords':["beginner", "beginning", "regretted", "regretting", "visited", "visiting", "inferred", "inference", "offered", "forgetting"]},
    {'id':"y3-t4-w4-l1",'year':"Y3",'term':"T4",     'week':4,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':"Sequence 7",'lesson':"Lesson 1",     'focus':"adding the -ly suffix: -ic words take -ally",     'explanation':"When we add -ly to most words, we just put -ly on the end. But if the root word ends in -ic, we use -ally instead of just -ly. For example, magic becomes magically, and frantic becomes frantically.",     'hlWords':["logically", "completely", "usually", "frantically", "weekly", "perfectly", "classically", "honestly", "artistically", "organically"]},
    {'id':"y3-t4-w4-l2",'year':"Y3",'term':"T4",     'week':4,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':"Sequence 7",'lesson':"Lesson 2",     'focus':"adding the -ly suffix: y to i and -le to -ly changes",     'explanation':"When a root word ends in y, we change the y to i before adding -ly, so happy becomes happily. When a root word ends in -le, we swap -le for -ly, so gentle becomes gently. These small changes help the word sound and look right.",     'hlWords':["guiltily", "ordinarily", "subtly", "easily", "humbly", "angrily", "twinkly", "flexibly", "steadily", "necessarily"]},
    {'id':"y3-t4-w4-l3",'year':"Y3",'term':"T4",     'week':4,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':"Sequence 7",'lesson':"Lesson 3",     'focus':"adding the -ly suffix: consolidating all rules",     'explanation':"There are three key rules for adding -ly: if the word ends in -le, swap -le for -ly; if it ends in -ic, add -ally; if it ends in y, change y to i then add -ly. For all other words, simply add -ly to the end.",     'hlWords':["wrinkly", "crumbly", "twinkly", "basically", "musically", "organically", "luckily", "easily", "happily", "dramatically"]},
    {'id':"y3-t4-w5-l1",'year':"Y3",'term':"T4",     'week':5,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':"Sequence 7",'lesson':"Lesson 4",     'focus':"adding the -ous suffix, including -ge words that keep the e",     'explanation':"The suffix -ous is added to nouns to make adjectives meaning 'full of'. For most words, simply add -ous, but if the word ends in e, remove the e first. However, if the word ends in -ge, keep the e so the g keeps its soft sound — for example, outrage becomes outrageous.",     'hlWords':["carnivorous", "hazardous", "advantageous", "joyous", "gorgeous", "famous", "mountainous", "adventurous", "outrageous", "continuous"]},
    {'id':"y3-t4-w5-l2",'year':"Y3",'term':"T4",     'week':5,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':"Sequence 7",'lesson':"Lesson 5",     'focus':"adding the -ous suffix: y to i and -our to -or changes",     'explanation':"When a root word ends in y, change the y to i before adding -ous, so vary becomes various. When a root word ends in -our, change -our to -or before adding -ous, so humour becomes humorous. Some words have no clear root, so we just complete them with -ous.",     'hlWords':["various", "rigorous", "luminous", "victorious", "furious", "ominous", "vaporous", "generous", "harmonious", "humorous"]},
    {'id':"y3-t4-w5-l3",'year':"Y3",'term':"T4",     'week':5,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':"Sequence 7",'lesson':"Lesson 6",     'focus':"adding the -ous suffix: consolidating all rules",     'explanation':"The suffix -ous turns nouns into adjectives meaning 'full of'. Remember to remove the e if the root ends in e, keep the e if the root ends in -ge, change y to i if the root ends in y, and change -our to -or if the root ends in -our.",     'hlWords':["famous", "nervous", "adventurous", "poisonous", "hazardous", "dangerous", "furious", "glamorous", "outrageous", "carnivorous"]},
    {'id':"y3-t5-w1-l1",'year':"Y3",'term':"T5",     'week':1,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':"Sequence 8",'lesson':"Lesson 1",     'focus':"tion / sion / ssion / cian",     'explanation':"The suffix -tion is used when the root word ends in t or te (e.g. invent → invention, educate → education). This lesson introduces the -tion pattern, helping pupils recognise that the root word's final letters are the key signal for selecting this spelling of the 'shun' sound.",     'hlWords':["election", "adoption", "eruption", "selection", "invention", "education", "donation", "collection", "operation", "direction"]},
    {'id':"y3-t5-w1-l2",'year':"Y3",'term':"T5",     'week':1,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':"Sequence 8",'lesson':"Lesson 2",     'focus':"tion / sion / ssion / cian",     'explanation':"The suffix -sion is used when the root word ends in d, de, or se (e.g. extend → extension, invade → invasion, confuse → confusion). This lesson focuses on the -sion pattern so pupils can identify the root word ending as the signal for choosing this spelling of 'shun'.",     'hlWords':["extension", "expansion", "ascension", "version", "invasion", "explosion", "division", "confusion", "conclusion", "decision"]},
    {'id':"y3-t5-w1-l3",'year':"Y3",'term':"T5",     'week':1,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':"Sequence 8",'lesson':"Lesson 3",     'focus':"tion / sion / ssion / cian",     'explanation':"Pupils apply both -tion and -sion patterns in the same lesson, choosing the correct suffix by examining the root word's final letters. They also encounter -sion words from se-ending roots (e.g. televise → television, revise → revision), extending their understanding before -ssion and -cian are introduced.",     'hlWords':["eruption", "rotation", "animation", "provision", "expansion", "television", "election", "revision", "pollution", "inclusion"]},
    {'id':"y3-t5-w2-l1",'year':"Y3",'term':"T5",     'week':2,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':"Sequence 8",'lesson':"Lesson 4",     'focus':"tion / sion / ssion / cian",     'explanation':"The suffix -ssion is used when the root word ends in ss or mit (e.g. pass → passion, admit → admission). This lesson focuses on the -ssion pattern, helping pupils see that the double s in the suffix reflects the double s or t of the root word ending.",     'hlWords':["mission", "impression", "obsession", "admission", "discussion", "passion", "permission", "possession", "expression", "transmission"]},
    {'id':"y3-t5-w2-l2",'year':"Y3",'term':"T5",     'week':2,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':"Sequence 8",'lesson':"Lesson 5",     'focus':"tion / sion / ssion / cian",     'explanation':"The suffix -cian is used when the root word ends in c or cs (e.g. music → musician, electric → electrician). It usually denotes a profession or skill. This lesson focuses on recognising the -cian pattern and associating it with job titles derived from nouns ending in c.",     'hlWords':["musician", "logician", "clinician", "technician", "politician", "electrician", "magician", "optician", "mathematician", "beautician"]},
    {'id':"y3-t5-w2-l3",'year':"Y3",'term':"T5",     'week':2,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':"Sequence 8",'lesson':"Lesson 6",     'focus':"tion / sion / ssion / cian",     'explanation':"The 'shun' sound can be spelled -tion, -sion, -ssion, or -cian; the correct suffix is determined by the root word's ending: t/te → -tion, d/de/se → -sion, ss/mit → -ssion, and c/cs → -cian (usually for professions).",     'hlWords':["impression", "expression", "mission", "physician", "magician", "permission", "discussion", "admission", "clinician", "obsession"]},
    {'id':"y3-t5-w3-l1",'year':"Y3",'term':"T5",     'week':3,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':"Sequence 8",'lesson':"Lesson 7",     'focus':"tion / sion / ssion / cian",     'explanation':"Children apply the rule that the 'shun' suffix is spelled according to the root word's ending — practising with words such as magic → magician, invade → invasion, discuss → discussion, and admit → admission.",     'hlWords':["magician", "invasion", "discussion", "admission", "adoption", "tension", "infection", "obsession", "division", "conclusion"]},
    {'id':"y3-t5-w3-l2",'year':"Y3",'term':"T5",     'week':3,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':"Sequence 8",'lesson':"Lesson 8",     'focus':"tion / sion / ssion / cian",     'explanation':"Continuing practice of the four 'shun' suffixes, children transform root words such as invent → invention, operate → operation, persuade → persuasion, possess → possession, and physics → physician.",     'hlWords':["invention", "physician", "permission", "possession", "operation", "persuasion", "magician", "confusion", "prediction", "profession"]},
    {'id':"y3-t5-w3-l3",'year':"Y3",'term':"T5",     'week':3,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':"Sequence 8",'lesson':"Lesson 9",     'focus':"tion / sion / ssion / cian",     'explanation':"A consolidation lesson on the four 'shun' suffixes, focusing on trickier root words: expand → expansion, optic → optician, explode → explosion, submit → submission, and educate → education.",     'hlWords':["expansion", "optician", "education", "explosion", "objection", "submission", "animation", "politician", "obsession", "connection"]},
    {'id':"y3-t5-w4-l1",'year':"Y3",'term':"T5",     'week':4,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':"Sequence 9",'lesson':"Lesson 1",     'focus':"LKS2 Word List",     'explanation':"The quadgraphs 'eigh' and 'aigh' (four-letter graphemes) usually represent the long 'a' sound, as in eight, weight, and straight; 'height' is an exception where 'eigh' produces the long 'i' sound instead.",     'hlWords':["eight", "eighth", "weight", "straight", "height", "eighteen", "eighty", "weigh", "straighten", "lightweight"]},
    {'id':"y3-t5-w4-l2",'year':"Y3",'term':"T5",     'week':4,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':"Sequence 9",'lesson':"Lesson 2",     'focus':"LKS2 Word List",     'explanation':"The quadgraph 'ough' represents at least five different sounds across these statutory words: long 'o' in though/although, 'uff' in enough, 'oo' in through, and 'aw' in thought — children must learn each word individually.",     'hlWords':["though", "although", "enough", "thought", "through", "bought", "brought", "ought", "fought", "thorough"]},
    {'id':"y3-t5-w4-l3",'year':"Y3",'term':"T5",     'week':4,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':"Sequence 9",'lesson':"Lesson 3",     'focus':"LKS2 Word List",     'explanation':"This lesson targets three unusual patterns: the 'augh' quadgraph representing 'aw' in caught and daughter, the rare 'ngth' consonant cluster in length and strength, and the word strange where 'g' spells the 'j' sound.",     'hlWords':["caught", "length", "strength", "strange", "daughter", "taught", "naughty", "lengthy", "strengthen", "stranger"]},
    {'id':"y3-t5-w5-l1",'year':"Y3",'term':"T5",     'week':5,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':"Sequence 9",'lesson':"Lesson 4",     'focus':"LKS2 Word List",     'explanation':"Breath (noun, no final e) and breathe (verb, with silent e) differ by one letter but are different word classes; woman (singular, spelled with 'a') and women (plural, spelled with 'e') are irregular forms that must be memorised.",     'hlWords':["breath", "breathe", "woman", "women", "breathless", "breathing", "breathtaking", "breathed", "breathes", "womanly"]},
    {'id':"y3-t5-w5-l2",'year':"Y3",'term':"T5",     'week':5,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':"Sequence 9",'lesson':"Lesson 5",     'focus':"LKS2 Word List",     'explanation':"The statutory words complete, describe, extreme, and separate all end with a split digraph where the silent 'e' makes the preceding vowel long; separate is also tricky because it contains the 'er' sound spelled 'ar'.",     'hlWords':["complete", "describe", "extreme", "separate", "compete", "admire", "provide", "confuse", "suppose", "compose"]},
    {'id':"y3-t5-w5-l3",'year':"Y3",'term':"T5",     'week':5,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':"Sequence 9",'lesson':"Lesson 6",     'focus':"LKS2 Word List",     'explanation':"Unlike the previous lesson's split digraph words, imagine, medicine, notice, and promise appear to end in a split digraph but the final 'e' is silent and the other vowel makes a short 'i' sound rather than a long vowel.",     'hlWords':["imagine", "medicine", "notice", "promise", "village", "engine", "orange", "palace", "practice", "surface"]},
    {'id':"y3-t6-w1-l1",'year':"Y3",'term':"T6",     'week':1,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':"Sequence 9",'lesson':"Lesson 7",     'focus':"words ending -sion",     'explanation':"The '-sion' suffix (pronounced 'zh-un') forms nouns from verbs: when the verb ends in '-se', drop 'se' and add 'sion' (supervise → supervision); when it ends in '-de', drop 'de' and add 'sion' (invade → invasion).",     'hlWords':["explosion", "invasion", "version", "collision", "decision", "supervision", "revision", "confusion", "division", "television"]},
    {'id':"y3-t6-w1-l2",'year':"Y3",'term':"T6",     'week':1,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':"Sequence 9",'lesson':"Lesson 8",     'focus':"words ending -sion",     'explanation':"Continued practice of the '-sion' suffix rule: verbs ending '-se' drop 'se' and take 'sion' (diffuse → diffusion, confuse → confusion), and verbs ending '-de' drop 'de' and take 'sion' (divide → division, conclude → conclusion).",     'hlWords':["diffusion", "conclusion", "revision", "confusion", "provision", "division", "decision", "television", "collision", "invasion"]},
    {'id':"y3-t6-w1-l3",'year':"Y3",'term':"T6",     'week':1,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':"Sequence 9",'lesson':"Lesson 9",     'focus':"words ending -sion",     'explanation':"A mastery lesson consolidating the '-sion' suffix pattern; children apply the rule independently and explain the transformation — for example, the verb collide becomes the noun collision by replacing '-de' with '-sion'.",     'hlWords':["revision", "conclusion", "version", "collision", "explosion", "invasion", "confusion", "division", "television", "supervision"]},
    {'id':"y3-t6-w2-l1",'year':"Y3",'term':"T6",     'week':2,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':"Mastery 4",'lesson':"Lesson 1",     'focus':"i sound spelled y",     'explanation':"In some words the short 'i' sound is spelled with the letter 'y' rather than 'i'; there is no reliable rule, but 'y' for short 'i' often appears after 's' at the start of a word (syrup, symbol, syllable) or near the letter 'm' (rhythm, hymn).",     'hlWords':["syrup", "mystery", "synonym", "gym", "hymn", "symbol", "symmetry", "syllable", "rhythm", "mystical"]},
    {'id':"y3-t6-w2-l2",'year':"Y3",'term':"T6",     'week':2,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':"Mastery 4",'lesson':"Lesson 2",     'focus':"i sound spelled y",     'explanation':"Words such as myth, crystal, and pyramid all contain the short 'i' sound spelled 'y'; children learn to identify these words in context and explain why other words with a short 'i' sound use the letter 'i' instead.",     'hlWords':["myth", "crystal", "pyramid", "symbol", "gym", "rhythm", "symmetry", "syllable", "hymn", "mystical"]},
    {'id':"y3-t6-w2-l3",'year':"Y3",'term':"T6",     'week':2,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':"Mastery 4",'lesson':"Lesson 3",     'focus':"i sound spelled y",     'explanation':"The letter 'y' can represent the short 'i' sound (symptom, cylinder, system) or the long 'i' sound (cycle, cygnet); children distinguish between these uses and identify which words contain 'y' for short 'i'.",     'hlWords':["symptom", "system", "cylinder", "symmetry", "symbol", "gym", "rhythm", "hymn", "myth", "synonym"]},
    {'id':"y3-t6-w3-l1",'year':"Y3",'term':"T6",     'week':3,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':"Mastery 5",'lesson':"Lesson 1",     'focus':"alternative long a sounds",     'explanation':"The long 'a' sound can be spelled 'ei' (usually mid-word: veil, rein, beige), 'eigh' (in various positions: weight, neighbour), or 'ey' (usually end of word: survey, obey, grey); children practise selecting the correct grapheme.",     'hlWords':["veil", "convey", "weight", "survey", "reindeer", "beige", "obey", "neighbour", "rein", "grey"]},
    {'id':"y3-t6-w3-l2",'year':"Y3",'term':"T6",     'week':3,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':"Mastery 5",'lesson':"Lesson 2",     'focus':"alternative long a sounds",     'explanation':"Children spot and correct misspellings of long 'a' words, applying the patterns: 'ei' mid-word (beige, veil), 'eigh' in words like neighbour and eight, and 'ey' at the end of words such as obey, prey, and grey.",     'hlWords':["obey", "beige", "neighbour", "reindeer", "prey", "veil", "convey", "grey", "rein", "eight"]},
    {'id':"y3-t6-w3-l3",'year':"Y3",'term':"T6",     'week':3,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':"Mastery 5",'lesson':"Lesson 3",     'focus':"alternative long a sounds",     'explanation':"Children explore words built from the root 'weigh' (outweigh, weightless, overweight) and 'eight' (eighteen, eighty, eighths), seeing how the 'eigh' grapheme extends into related vocabulary; 'disobey' and 'neighbourhood' extend the 'ey'/'eigh' patterns.",     'hlWords':["eighteen", "eighty", "eighths", "weighed", "disobey", "neighbourhood", "outweigh", "weightless", "overweight", "reindeer"]},
    {'id':"y3-t6-w4-l1",'year':"Y3",'term':"T6",     'week':4,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':"Mastery 6",'lesson':"Lesson 1",     'focus':"tion/sion/ssion/cian",     'explanation':"A mastery lesson revising all four 'shun' suffixes: -tion after t/te (election, operation), -sion after d/de/se (invasion, persuasion), -ssion after ss/mit, and -cian after c/cs for professions (magician); children transform root words by applying the correct suffix.",     'hlWords':["election", "tension", "operation", "invasion", "persuasion", "promotion", "animation", "expansion", "invention", "magician"]},
    {'id':"y3-t6-w4-l2",'year':"Y3",'term':"T6",     'week':4,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':"Mastery 6",'lesson':"Lesson 2",     'focus':"tion/sion/ssion/cian",     'explanation':"The suffixes -tion, -sion, -ssion and -cian all make the 'shun' sound; this lesson consolidates all four choices, with particular focus on -ssion (root ends ss/mit) and -cian (root ends c/cs, usually a profession such as musician or politician).",     'hlWords':["musician", "possession", "impression", "magician", "submission", "politician", "admission", "commission", "permission", "obsession"]},
    {'id':"y3-t6-w4-l3",'year':"Y3",'term':"T6",     'week':4,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':"Mastery 6",'lesson':"Lesson 3",     'focus':"tion/sion/ssion/cian",     'explanation':"Pupils apply their understanding of all four 'shun' suffixes to words in context, selecting the correct suffix by identifying the root word ending — for example, pollute becomes pollution (-tion), obsess becomes obsession (-ssion), and electric becomes electrician (-cian).",     'hlWords':["pollution", "electrician", "obsession", "commission", "completion", "decision", "admission", "expression", "collection", "invasion"]},
    {'id':"y3-t6-w5-l1",'year':"Y3",'term':"T6",     'week':5,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':"Mastery 7",'lesson':"Lesson 1",     'focus':"LKS2 Word List",     'explanation':"Four statutory words contain the 'ear' grapheme: in early, earth, learn and heard it represents the /er/ sound, while in heart it represents the /ar/ sound; guide and guard contain a silent 'u' after the letter 'g'.",     'hlWords':["early", "earth", "learn", "heart", "guide", "guard", "heard", "search", "earn", "pearl"]},
    {'id':"y3-t6-w5-l2",'year':"Y3",'term':"T6",     'week':5,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':"Mastery 7",'lesson':"Lesson 2",     'focus':"LKS2 Word List",     'explanation':"Each of these statutory words contains a silent letter that is easily missed: build (silent u), answer (silent w), island (silent s), often (silent t), interest (silent e), history (silent o), natural (silent u), and knowledge (silent k and w).",     'hlWords':["build", "answer", "island", "often", "interest", "history", "natural", "knowledge", "knife", "castle"]},
    {'id':"y3-t6-w5-l3",'year':"Y3",'term':"T6",     'week':5,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':"Mastery 7",'lesson':"Lesson 3",     'focus':"LKS2 Word List",     'explanation':"Each of these statutory words has a tricky hidden challenge: believe contains ie for the long e sound, business derives from busy, favourite hides the word 'our', February needs the medial r, library has two r sounds, and forward contains the word 'for'.",     'hlWords':["believe", "business", "favourite", "february", "library", "forward", "although", "describe", "probably", "thought"]},
    {'id':"y4-t1-w1-l1",'year':"Y4",'term':"T1",     'week':1,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':"Revisit",'lesson':"Lesson 1",     'focus':"doubling consonants",     'explanation':"When a word of more than one syllable ends in a single short vowel plus a consonant and the final syllable is stressed, double the consonant before adding a vowel suffix; if the stress falls on an earlier syllable, simply add the suffix without doubling.",     'hlWords':["referred", "preferring", "committed", "beginner", "forgetting", "inferred", "referral", "covering", "listening", "gardener"]},
    {'id':"y4-t1-w1-l2",'year':"Y4",'term':"T1",     'week':1,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':"Revisit",'lesson':"Lesson 2",     'focus':"doubling consonants",     'explanation':"Pupils revisit the doubling rule by focusing on words where the stressed final syllable triggers doubling before a vowel suffix (transmitting, regretted, occurrence) and contrast them with unstressed-final-syllable words that do not double (focusing, happening, covered).",     'hlWords':["transmitting", "committed", "inferring", "regretted", "occurrence", "equipped", "transferred", "preferred", "focusing", "happening"]},
    {'id':"y4-t1-w1-l3",'year':"Y4",'term':"T1",     'week':1,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':"Revisit",'lesson':"Lesson 3",     'focus':"doubling consonants",     'explanation':"This lesson consolidates the doubling rule using pairs such as prefer/preferred and prefer/preference, showing that the same root word may or may not trigger doubling depending on whether the suffix is a vowel suffix and the stress pattern of the root.",     'hlWords':["preferred", "preference", "benefitting", "occurred", "admitting", "controlled", "transferring", "forgotten", "beginning", "equipped"]},
    {'id':"y4-t1-w2-l1",'year':"Y4",'term':"T1",     'week':2,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':"Revisit",'lesson':"Lesson 4",     'focus':"adding the -ly suffix",     'explanation':"Most words simply take -ly, but three key exceptions apply: if the root ends in y, change y to i before adding -ly (grumpy → grumpily); if the root ends in -le, swap -le for -ly (simple → simply); if the root ends in -ic, use -ally (magic → magically).",     'hlWords':["magically", "steadily", "easily", "grumpily", "sensibly", "simply", "angrily", "logically", "terribly", "basically"]},
    {'id':"y4-t1-w2-l2",'year':"Y4",'term':"T1",     'week':2,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':"Revisit",'lesson':"Lesson 5",     'focus':"adding the -ly suffix",     'explanation':"Pupils apply the -ly suffix rules across a wider range of root words, practising the y → i change (sleepy → sleepily, greedy → greedily), the -le → -ly swap (gentle → gently), and the -ic → -ally pattern (tragic → tragically, musical → musically).",     'hlWords':["quickly", "sleepily", "luckily", "tragically", "gently", "bravely", "musically", "clearly", "greedily", "honestly"]},
    {'id':"y4-t1-w2-l3",'year':"Y4",'term':"T1",     'week':2,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':"Revisit",'lesson':"Lesson 6",     'focus':"adding the -ous suffix",     'explanation':"The -ous suffix changes root words to adjectives: most roots simply take -ous (danger → dangerous), but if the root ends in y change it to i (fury → furious), remove a final e (nerve → nervous), change -our to -or (humour → humorous), or keep -ge before -ous (outrage → outrageous).",     'hlWords':["dangerous", "furious", "nervous", "outrageous", "humorous", "glorious", "adventurous", "poisonous", "courageous", "mysterious"]},
    {'id':"y4-t1-w3-l1",'year':"Y4",'term':"T1",     'week':3,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':"Revisit",'lesson':"Lesson 7",     'focus':"the suffixes -tion/-sion/-ssion/-cian",     'explanation':"The 'shun' sound is spelled -tion when the root ends in t or te (erupt → eruption, populate → population) and -sion when the root ends in d, de or se (invade → invasion, confuse → confusion); pupils practise choosing between the two most common options.",     'hlWords':["calculation", "election", "confusion", "division", "vacation", "creation", "explosion", "injection", "invasion", "selection"]},
    {'id':"y4-t1-w3-l2",'year':"Y4",'term':"T1",     'week':3,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':"Revisit",'lesson':"Lesson 8",     'focus':"the suffixes -tion/-sion/-ssion/-cian",     'explanation':"Building on -tion and -sion, this lesson introduces -ssion for roots ending in ss or mit (admit → admission, express → expression) and reviews all three alongside -tion, asking pupils to identify the correct suffix from the root word ending.",     'hlWords':["provision", "permission", "admission", "extension", "expression", "rotation", "discussion", "location", "conclusion", "interaction"]},
    {'id':"y4-t1-w3-l3",'year':"Y4",'term':"T1",     'week':3,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':"Revisit",'lesson':"Lesson 9",     'focus':"the suffixes -tion/-sion/-ssion/-cian",     'explanation':"This lesson consolidates all four 'shun' spellings, with particular focus on -cian (root ends in c or cs, usually a profession: musician, mathematician, electrician, magician) alongside -tion, -sion and -ssion in context.",     'hlWords':["musician", "politician", "mathematician", "electrician", "magician", "expansion", "connection", "collection", "animation", "permission"]},
    {'id':"y4-t1-w4-l1",'year':"Y4",'term':"T1",     'week':4,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':"Sequence 1",'lesson':"Lesson 1",     'focus':"prefixes",     'explanation':"The prefixes un-, dis- and mis- all change the meaning of a root word: un- means 'not' or 'reverse' (untrue, unwell), dis- means 'the opposite of' or 'not' (disorder, disagree), and mis- means 'wrongly' or 'badly' (mismatch, mislead).",     'hlWords':["unwell", "untrue", "unclear", "mismatch", "miscount", "mislead", "disorder", "disagree", "disappear", "misplace"]},
    {'id':"y4-t1-w4-l2",'year':"Y4",'term':"T1",     'week':4,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':"Sequence 1",'lesson':"Lesson 2",     'focus':"prefixes",     'explanation':"Pupils continue practising un-, dis- and mis- by applying them to new root words, noticing that the prefix is added directly to the root without any spelling change to either part — for example, dis + allow = disallow, not disallow with a letter changed.",     'hlWords':["unusual", "uncommon", "uncover", "unlikely", "misguide", "misread", "mistreat", "disallow", "disgrace", "disconnect"]},
    {'id':"y4-t1-w4-l3",'year':"Y4",'term':"T1",     'week':4,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':"Sequence 1",'lesson':"Lesson 3",     'focus':"prefixes",     'explanation':"This lesson extends un-, dis- and mis- to trickier root words, including mis- + spell = misspell (note the double s where prefix and root meet) and mis- + shape = misshape, helping pupils see that both letters are retained when the prefix ends and root begins with the same letter.",     'hlWords':["misspell", "misspeak", "mislabel", "misshape", "unsure", "unpopular", "untidy", "disloyal", "disprove", "disappear"]},
    {'id':"y4-t1-w5-l1",'year':"Y4",'term':"T1",     'week':5,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':"Sequence 1",'lesson':"Lesson 4",     'focus':"prefixes",     'explanation':"The prefixes in-, il-, im- and ir- all mean 'not'; the choice depends on the first letter of the root word: il- before l (illegible), ir- before r (irregular), im- before m or p (immobile, impersonal), and in- before most other letters (inactive, incomplete).",     'hlWords':["inactive", "insecure", "invisible", "incomplete", "impersonal", "immobile", "irrelevant", "irregular", "illegible", "illogical"]},
    {'id':"y4-t1-w5-l2",'year':"Y4",'term':"T1",     'week':5,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':"Sequence 1",'lesson':"Lesson 5",     'focus':"prefixes",     'explanation':"Pupils practise selecting between in-/il-/im-/ir- by matching each prefix to root words beginning with l, r, m/p or other letters, consolidating the pattern that the prefix letter echoes the opening letter of l- and r-roots to create a double letter.",     'hlWords':["irrational", "irresponsible", "illiterate", "impatient", "impolite", "inaccurate", "infrequent", "incomplete", "impossible", "insensitive"]},
    {'id':"y4-t1-w5-l3",'year':"Y4",'term':"T1",     'week':5,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':"Sequence 1",'lesson':"Lesson 6",     'focus':"prefixes",     'explanation':"This lesson consolidates all four in-/il-/im-/ir- prefix variants through matching to definitions and applying them in sentences, drawing attention to the double letters created when im- or ir- is added to roots beginning with m or r (immovable, irresistible, irrational).",     'hlWords':["indefinite", "immovable", "irresistible", "irrational", "impersonal", "illiterate", "insensitive", "immeasurable", "immoral", "invisible"]},
    {'id':"y4-t2-w1-l1",'year':"Y4",'term':"T2",     'week':1,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':"Sequence 2",'lesson':"Lesson 1",     'focus':"Homophones: your / you're",     'explanation':"\"Your\" is a possessive pronoun showing something belongs to you; \"you're\" is a contraction of \"you are\" — the apostrophe marks the missing letter \"a\". Children must use meaning and grammar to choose the correct form.",     'hlWords':["your", "you're", "your", "you're", "your", "you're", "your", "you're", "your", "you're"]},
    {'id':"y4-t2-w1-l2",'year':"Y4",'term':"T2",     'week':1,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':"Sequence 2",'lesson':"Lesson 2",     'focus':"Homophones: there / their / they're",     'explanation':"Three homophones with different meanings and spellings: \"there\" refers to a place; \"their\" shows possession (it belongs to them); \"they're\" is a contraction of \"they are\". Children must identify meaning in context to choose the correct form.",     'hlWords':["there", "their", "they're", "there", "their", "they're", "there", "their", "they're", "there"]},
    {'id':"y4-t2-w1-l3",'year':"Y4",'term':"T2",     'week':1,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':"Sequence 2",'lesson':"Lesson 3",     'focus':"Homophones: of / off",     'explanation':"\"Of\" is a preposition showing belonging, connection, or origin (e.g. the colour of the sky); \"off\" indicates separation, removal, or distance from something (e.g. brushed off the crumbs). Children choose the correct form based on meaning.",     'hlWords':["of", "off", "of", "off", "of", "off", "of", "off", "of", "off"]},
    {'id':"y4-t2-w2-l1",'year':"Y4",'term':"T2",     'week':2,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':"Sequence 2",'lesson':"Lesson 4",     'focus':"Homophones: break / brake",     'explanation':"\"Break\" means to separate into pieces or to take a pause; \"brake\" is a device that slows something down — both words can be used as a noun or a verb. Children use sentence meaning to decide which spelling is correct.",     'hlWords':["break", "brake", "break", "brake", "break", "brake", "break", "brake", "break", "brake"]},
    {'id':"y4-t2-w2-l2",'year':"Y4",'term':"T2",     'week':2,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':"Sequence 2",'lesson':"Lesson 5",     'focus':"Homophones: piece / peace",     'explanation':"\"Piece\" is a single part of a whole and often follows words like \"a\" or \"one\"; \"peace\" is a noun describing a state of calm or absence of conflict. Both are nouns — children use context and meaning to select the correct spelling.",     'hlWords':["piece", "peace", "piece", "peace", "piece", "peace", "piece", "peace", "piece", "peace"]},
    {'id':"y4-t2-w2-l3",'year':"Y4",'term':"T2",     'week':2,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':"Sequence 2",'lesson':"Lesson 6",     'focus':"Homophones: rain / reign / rein",     'explanation':"Three homophones with distinct meanings: \"rain\" is water falling from the sky; \"reign\" means to rule as a monarch; \"rein\" is a strap used to control a horse. Children must identify the meaning in context to choose the correct spelling.",     'hlWords':["rain", "reign", "rein", "rain", "reign", "rein", "rain", "reign", "rein", "rain"]},
    {'id':"y4-t2-w3-l1",'year':"Y4",'term':"T2",     'week':3,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':"Sequence 2",'lesson':"Lesson 7",     'focus':"Homophones: accept / except",     'explanation':"\"Accept\" is a verb meaning to receive or agree to something; \"except\" is a preposition meaning \"not including\" or \"other than\". The similar sounds make these easy to confuse — children must focus on the meaning of the sentence to choose correctly.",     'hlWords':["accept", "except", "accept", "except", "accept", "except", "accept", "except", "accept", "except"]},
    {'id':"y4-t2-w3-l2",'year':"Y4",'term':"T2",     'week':3,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':"Sequence 2",'lesson':"Lesson 8",     'focus':"Homophones: weather / whether",     'explanation':"\"Weather\" refers to outdoor atmospheric conditions (sun, rain, wind); \"whether\" is a conjunction used to introduce a choice or express doubt. The two words look and sound very similar, so children must use sentence meaning to decide which is correct.",     'hlWords':["weather", "whether", "weather", "whether", "weather", "whether", "weather", "whether", "weather", "whether"]},
    {'id':"y4-t2-w3-l3",'year':"Y4",'term':"T2",     'week':3,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':"Sequence 2",'lesson':"Lesson 9",     'focus':"Homophones: effect / affect",     'explanation':"\"Effect\" is usually a noun meaning the result of something (often paired with had/has/have); \"affect\" is usually a verb meaning to influence or change something. Children are taught to check the word's grammatical role in the sentence to choose correctly.",     'hlWords':["affect", "effect", "affect", "effect", "affect", "effect", "affect", "effect", "affect", "effect"]},
    {'id':"y4-t2-w4-l1",'year':"Y4",'term':"T2",     'week':4,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':"Sequence 3",'lesson':"Lesson 1",     'focus':"Words ending -sure / -ture",     'explanation':"The ending -sure makes a /zhuh/ sound (soft z + schwa), as in measure and leisure; the ending -ture makes a /chuh/ sound (ch + schwa), as in fracture and adventure. There is no fixed spelling rule — children learn these words by their distinct sounds.",     'hlWords':["measure", "leisure", "enclosure", "fracture", "lecture", "structure", "capture", "adventure", "texture", "treasure"]},
    {'id':"y4-t2-w4-l2",'year':"Y4",'term':"T2",     'week':4,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':"Sequence 3",'lesson':"Lesson 2",     'focus':"Words ending -sure / -ture",     'explanation':"Practising adding the correct ending: -sure (making a /zhuh/ sound) or -ture (making a /chuh/ sound). Children complete stems with the right ending and distinguish between words such as disclosure and sculpture, pleasure and puncture.",     'hlWords':["disclosure", "feature", "sculpture", "nurture", "measure", "pleasure", "furniture", "culture", "puncture", "departure"]},
    {'id':"y4-t2-w4-l3",'year':"Y4",'term':"T2",     'week':4,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':"Sequence 3",'lesson':"Lesson 3",     'focus':"Words ending -sure / -ture",     'explanation':"A useful pattern: -sure typically follows a vowel (measure, treasure, pleasure), while -ture typically follows a consonant (fracture, adventure, nurture). This pattern does not cover every word but gives children a helpful starting point for choosing the correct ending.",     'hlWords':["measure", "treasure", "pleasure", "creature", "feature", "enclosure", "fracture", "adventure", "nurture", "moisture"]},
    {'id':"y4-t2-w5-l1",'year':"Y4",'term':"T2",     'week':5,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':"Sequence 3",'lesson':"Lesson 4",     'focus':"Words ending -sure / -ture",     'explanation':"Some words ending in the /chuh/ sound are spelled -cher (teacher, voucher, preacher) rather than -ture; children learn to distinguish this pattern from -ture words such as fracture and culture by listening carefully to the word and learning its spelling.",     'hlWords':["teacher", "voucher", "preacher", "archer", "poacher", "fracture", "culture", "feature", "richer", "sculpture"]},
    {'id':"y4-t2-w5-l2",'year':"Y4",'term':"T2",     'week':5,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':"Sequence 3",'lesson':"Lesson 5",     'focus':"Words ending -sure / -ture",     'explanation':"Some words use the -tcher spelling (catcher, stretcher, pitcher, watcher), which creates the same /chuh/ sound as -ture but follows a different pattern. Children practise distinguishing -tcher words from -ture words by learning each word's spelling explicitly.",     'hlWords':["catcher", "stretcher", "watcher", "pitcher", "butcher", "mixture", "nature", "lecture", "venture", "switcher"]},
    {'id':"y4-t2-w5-l3",'year':"Y4",'term':"T2",     'week':5,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':"Sequence 3",'lesson':"Lesson 6",     'focus':"Words ending -sure / -ture",     'explanation':"Consolidation lesson bringing together all four endings: -sure (/zhuh/), -ture (/chuh/), -cher, and -tcher. Children apply their knowledge through dictation and sentence-level tasks, selecting the correct spelling for each word from memory.",     'hlWords':["teacher", "measure", "structure", "sketcher", "creature", "enclosure", "voucher", "stretcher", "pitcher", "catcher"]},
    {'id':"y4-t3-w1-l1",'year':"Y4",'term':"T3",     'week':1,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':"Sequence 4",'lesson':"Lesson 1",     'focus':"Prefixes",     'explanation':"The prefixes un- (not/reverse), dis- (opposite of/not), and mis- (wrongly/incorrectly) are added to the beginning of a root word to change its meaning; the spelling of the root word never changes when a prefix is added.",     'hlWords':["unhappy", "unclear", "disorder", "misprint", "unkind", "dishonest", "mislead", "disagree", "unwell", "misplace"]},
    {'id':"y4-t3-w1-l2",'year':"Y4",'term':"T3",     'week':1,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':"Sequence 4",'lesson':"Lesson 2",     'focus':"Prefixes",     'explanation':"The prefixes in-, il-, im-, and ir- all mean \"not\"; the form used depends on the first letter of the root word — il- before l (illegal), im- before b/m/p (impossible), ir- before r (irregular), and in- elsewhere (incomplete).",     'hlWords':["impatient", "illiterate", "indefinite", "irresponsible", "indirect", "irregular", "imperfect", "impossible", "illegal", "incomplete"]},
    {'id':"y4-t3-w1-l3",'year':"Y4",'term':"T3",     'week':1,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':"Sequence 4",'lesson':"Lesson 3",     'focus':"Prefixes",     'explanation':"Consolidation of negative prefixes: children identify which prefix — un-, in-, il-, im-, or ir- — creates the antonym of a given root word, applying knowledge of which prefix form matches the root word's opening letter.",     'hlWords':["uncertain", "irrelevant", "impossible", "unhappy", "uncommon", "unequal", "unclean", "irreversible", "impolite", "incomplete"]},
    {'id':"y4-t3-w2-l1",'year':"Y4",'term':"T3",     'week':2,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':"Sequence 4",'lesson':"Lesson 4",     'focus':"Words ending -sure / -ture",     'explanation':"Mastery lesson revisiting -sure and -ture words: children apply the correct endings in context, then identify misspelled words in a passage containing adventure, treasure, picture, creature, enclosure, measure, capture, and departure.",     'hlWords':["lecture", "exposure", "departure", "fracture", "measure", "adventure", "treasure", "picture", "creature", "capture"]},
    {'id':"y4-t3-w2-l2",'year':"Y4",'term':"T3",     'week':2,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':"Sequence 4",'lesson':"Lesson 5",     'focus':"Words ending -sure / -ture",     'explanation':"Mastery lesson revisiting -cher and -tcher words alongside -ture words: children identify misspellings in a passage containing pitcher, catcher, teacher, capture, and fracture, applying all four endings accurately from memory.",     'hlWords':["creature", "sketcher", "poacher", "richer", "sculpture", "stretcher", "pitcher", "catcher", "teacher", "fracture"]},
    {'id':"y4-t3-w2-l3",'year':"Y4",'term':"T3",     'week':2,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':"Sequence 4",'lesson':"Lesson 6",     'focus':"words ending sure/ture",     'explanation':"The -sure ending makes the /ʒə/ (zhuh) sound while -ture makes the /tʃə/ (chuh) sound; there is no rule to determine which ending a word uses, so pupils must learn each word individually, distinguishing the two sounds through careful oral pronunciation.",     'hlWords':["texture", "structure", "leisure", "creature", "departure", "enclosure", "adventure", "literature", "measure", "treasure"]},
    {'id':"y4-t3-w3-l1",'year':"Y4",'term':"T3",     'week':3,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':"Sequence 4",'lesson':"Lesson 7",     'focus':"LKS2 Word List",     'explanation':"These LKS2 statutory words all contain double consonants; a double consonant usually follows a short vowel sound, but not every short vowel requires doubling, so pupils must memorise exactly where the double consonant falls in each word.",     'hlWords':["accident", "appear", "arrive", "occasion", "opposite", "grammar", "address", "different", "possible", "possess"]},
    {'id':"y4-t3-w3-l2",'year':"Y4",'term':"T3",     'week':3,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':"Sequence 4",'lesson':"Lesson 8",     'focus':"LKS2 Word List",     'explanation':"Pupils look deeper at the tricky patterns within the double-consonant LKS2 words, including words with two pairs of doubles (address, possess), silent letters, and prefixes such as dis- in disappear, learning to identify and explain what makes each word challenging.",     'hlWords':["occasion", "disappear", "possess", "address", "grammar", "different", "difficult", "suppose", "pressure", "opposite"]},
    {'id':"y4-t3-w3-l3",'year':"Y4",'term':"T3",     'week':3,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':"Sequence 4",'lesson':"Lesson 9",     'focus':"LKS2 Word List",     'explanation':"Pupils apply and consolidate their knowledge of double-consonant LKS2 statutory words by spotting and correcting misspellings in connected text, demonstrating accurate recall of the full set including address, difficult, pressure, and suppose.",     'hlWords':["possess", "appear", "pressure", "occasion", "arrive", "address", "difficult", "possible", "opposite", "suppose"]},
    {'id':"y4-t3-w4-l1",'year':"Y4",'term':"T3",     'week':4,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':"Mastery 1",'lesson':"Lesson 1",     'focus':"LKS2 Word List",     'explanation':"These LKS2 statutory words all contain the /ɜː/ (er) sound at the end, spelled er, ar, or re; words of Latin or French origin typically use the ar spelling (e.g. calendar, grammar, popular), while er is the most common ending for native English words.",     'hlWords':["consider", "quarter", "remember", "particular", "peculiar", "popular", "regular", "calendar", "grammar", "centre"]},
    {'id':"y4-t3-w4-l2",'year':"Y4",'term':"T3",     'week':4,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':"Mastery 1",'lesson':"Lesson 2",     'focus':"LKS2 Word List",     'explanation':"These LKS2 words contain the /ɜː/ (er) sound near the beginning, spelled ur (purpose, surprise), ir (circle), or ear variant (certain, perhaps); pupils identify the specific grapheme used in each word and compare it with the more common er and ar endings.",     'hlWords':["perhaps", "purpose", "surprise", "circle", "certain", "exercise", "consider", "quarter", "peculiar", "calendar"]},
    {'id':"y4-t3-w4-l3",'year':"Y4",'term':"T3",     'week':4,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':"Mastery 1",'lesson':"Lesson 3",     'focus':"LKS2 Word List",     'explanation':"Pupils consolidate knowledge of the /ɜː/ (er) sound across both groups of LKS2 words, identifying the odd-one-out (grammar uses ar for a different reason) and applying all the variant graphemes — er, ar, re, ur, ir — in context.",     'hlWords':["consider", "quarter", "remember", "particular", "peculiar", "popular", "regular", "calendar", "centre", "perhaps"]},
    {'id':"y4-t3-w5-l1",'year':"Y4",'term':"T3",     'week':5,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':"Mastery 2",'lesson':"Lesson 1",     'focus':"LKS2 Word List",     'explanation':"These LKS2 statutory words contain the /s/ sound spelled c, which occurs when c comes before the letters e, i, or y; pupils identify this alternative grapheme across the set, recognising it in words such as bicycle, circle, century, and recent.",     'hlWords':["bicycle", "centre", "century", "certain", "circle", "decide", "exercise", "recent", "sentence", "pencil"]},
    {'id':"y4-t3-w5-l2",'year':"Y4",'term':"T3",     'week':5,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':"Mastery 2",'lesson':"Lesson 2",     'focus':"LKS2 Word List",     'explanation':"These LKS2 words each contain an alternative vowel or consonant spelling: /uː/ spelled ui (fruit, bruise), /z/ spelled s (busy, exercise), long e spelled ea (increase), the /ɜː/ sound spelled er (material), short i spelled u (minute), and /eə/ spelled ere (therefore).",     'hlWords':["group", "busy", "fruit", "increase", "material", "exercise", "minute", "potatoes", "therefore", "bruise"]},
    {'id':"y4-t3-w5-l3",'year':"Y4",'term':"T3",     'week':5,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':"Mastery 2",'lesson':"Lesson 3",     'focus':"LKS2 Word List",     'explanation':"Pupils review and correct the full set of LKS2 words with alternative spellings from the previous two lessons, practising all variant graphemes — c for /s/, sc for /s/, ui for /uː/, ea for long e, er for /ɪə/, u for short i, and ere for /eə/ — by spotting errors in each word.",     'hlWords':["certain", "material", "fruit", "minute", "therefore", "recent", "increase", "exercise", "decide", "century"]},
    {'id':"y4-t4-w1-l1",'year':"Y4",'term':"T4",     'week':1,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':"Sequence 4",'lesson':"Lesson 10",     'focus':"LKS2 Word List",     'explanation':"When a root word ends in -al, add -ly to form the adverb (actual → actually, occasional → occasionally); when a root word ends in -le, change the -le to -ly (probable → probably, possible → possibly); pupils apply these rules to a set of LKS2 statutory words.",     'hlWords':["actually", "occasionally", "accidentally", "probably", "possibly", "basically", "naturally", "especially", "automatically", "magically"]},
    {'id':"y4-t4-w1-l2",'year':"Y4",'term':"T4",     'week':1,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':"Sequence 4",'lesson':"Lesson 11",     'focus':"LKS2 Word List",     'explanation':"The -tion ending (sounding like 'shun') is the most common spelling; possession uses -ssion because its root ends in ss; the suffix -ous is added to nouns to form adjectives, dropping a final e first (fame → famous), and pupils learn these patterns from the LKS2 statutory word list.",     'hlWords':["mention", "position", "question", "possession", "famous", "various", "direction", "action", "dangerous", "enormous"]},
    {'id':"y4-t4-w1-l3",'year':"Y4",'term':"T4",     'week':1,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':"Sequence 4",'lesson':"Lesson 12",     'focus':"LKS2 Word List",     'explanation':"These LKS2 words end in common but tricky suffixes — -ence (sentence, experience), -ent (experiment, confident), -ant (important, pleasant), -cial (special), and -ary (ordinary) — and pupils identify similarities across words to help fix the correct ending in memory.",     'hlWords':["sentence", "experience", "experiment", "important", "special", "ordinary", "confident", "independent", "pleasant", "different"]},
    {'id':"y4-t4-w2-l1",'year':"Y4",'term':"T4",     'week':2,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':"Sequence 5",'lesson':"Lesson 1",     'focus':"Greek & French sounds",     'explanation':"The /k/ sound is spelled ch in words of Greek origin, frequently appearing in science and music vocabulary; there is no decodable rule, so pupils learn these words as a group, recognising that ch-for-k is a marker of Greek-derived vocabulary.",     'hlWords':["anchor", "chemist", "chorus", "orchid", "monarch", "chaos", "orchestra", "echo", "stomach", "character"]},
    {'id':"y4-t4-w2-l2",'year':"Y4",'term':"T4",     'week':2,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':"Sequence 5",'lesson':"Lesson 2",     'focus':"Greek & French sounds",     'explanation':"The /ʃ/ (sh) sound is spelled ch in words of French origin; this is distinct from the typical English ch sound, so pupils learn to recognise French-derived words as a group — including everyday words like chef and machine as well as more unusual borrowings like chauffeur and quiche.",     'hlWords':["chef", "brochure", "machine", "crochet", "parachute", "chauffeur", "chalet", "quiche", "charade", "champagne"]},
    {'id':"y4-t4-w2-l3",'year':"Y4",'term':"T4",     'week':2,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':"Sequence 5",'lesson':"Lesson 3",     'focus':"Greek & French sounds",     'explanation':"The /s/ sound is spelled sc in words of Greek or Latin origin, appearing most often before the letters e, i, or y; pupils spot this grapheme in words such as science, scissors, scent, and descend, learning them as a group rather than applying a phonics rule.",     'hlWords':["scent", "scissors", "muscle", "science", "descend", "scientist", "ascent", "scenic", "crescent", "scene"]},
    {'id':"y4-t4-w3-l1",'year':"Y4",'term':"T4",     'week':3,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':"Sequence 5",'lesson':"Lesson 4",     'focus':"Greek & French sounds",     'explanation':"Pupils revisit all three alternative spellings — ch for /k/ (Greek origin), ch for /ʃ/ (French origin), and sc for /s/ (Greek/Latin origin) — identifying the correct grapheme in a wider range of mixed words using their accumulated knowledge of each group.",     'hlWords':["parachute", "fascinate", "orchid", "monarch", "machine", "muscle", "scientist", "chemist", "crochet", "scissors"]},
    {'id':"y4-t4-w3-l2",'year':"Y4",'term':"T4",     'week':3,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':"Sequence 5",'lesson':"Lesson 5",     'focus':"Greek & French sounds",     'explanation':"Consolidation of all three alternative ch and sc patterns across a wider word set including chevron and discipline; pupils identify whether the ch or sc makes the /k/, /ʃ/, or /s/ sound in each word, drawing on their knowledge of Greek and French word origins.",     'hlWords':["discipline", "stomach", "chevron", "anchor", "chef", "character", "descend", "chorus", "scenery", "brochure"]},
    {'id':"y4-t4-w3-l3",'year':"Y4",'term':"T4",     'week':3,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':"Sequence 5",'lesson':"Lesson 6",     'focus':"Greek & French sounds",     'explanation':"Pupils identify the correct spelling of words containing alternative ch and sc graphemes by choosing between plausible misspellings, reinforcing that ch-for-k, ch-for-sh, and sc-for-s patterns cannot be decoded and must be memorised as Greek- and French-origin spellings.",     'hlWords':["chemist", "character", "stomach", "technology", "fascinated", "chorus", "machine", "scissors", "science", "brochure"]},
    {'id':"y4-t4-w4-l1",'year':"Y4",'term':"T4",     'week':4,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':"Sequence 6",'lesson':"Lesson 1",     'focus':"prefixes",     'explanation':"The prefix re- (meaning 'again' or 'back') and sub- (meaning 'under') are added to root words with no change to the spelling of either the prefix or the root; understanding the meaning of each prefix helps pupils decode and spell a wide range of new words independently.",     'hlWords':["submarine", "reschedule", "reprint", "subheading", "redecorate", "submerge", "rewrite", "reappear", "subway", "rebuild"]},
    {'id':"y4-t4-w4-l2",'year':"Y4",'term':"T4",     'week':4,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':"Sequence 6",'lesson':"Lesson 2",     'focus':"prefixes",     'explanation':"The prefixes super- ('above/beyond') and inter- ('between') are added to the start of root words without any spelling change to the root; for example, super + market = supermarket and inter + city = intercity.",     'hlWords':["intercity", "internet", "international", "superhero", "supermarket", "superglue", "superpower", "superstar", "interlink", "interact"]},
    {'id':"y4-t4-w4-l3",'year':"Y4",'term':"T4",     'week':4,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':"Sequence 6",'lesson':"Lesson 3",     'focus':"prefixes",     'explanation':"The prefixes anti- ('against/opposite') and auto- ('self/own') are added to the start of root words without any spelling change to the root; for example, anti + social = antisocial and auto + graph = autograph.",     'hlWords':["antisocial", "antifreeze", "antihero", "anticlockwise", "antivirus", "autograph", "autobiography", "autopilot", "autocorrect", "automatic"]},
    {'id':"y4-t4-w5-l1",'year':"Y4",'term':"T4",     'week':5,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':"Sequence 6",'lesson':"Lesson 4",     'focus':"prefixes",     'explanation':"Pupils consolidate all six prefixes — re- (again), sub- (under), super- (above/beyond), inter- (between), anti- (against), auto- (self) — choosing the correct prefix for a given root word, with no change made to the root spelling.",     'hlWords':["superman", "reappear", "antigravity", "subtitle", "interlink", "autograph", "superglue", "subheading", "antifreeze", "antisocial"]},
    {'id':"y4-t4-w5-l2",'year':"Y4",'term':"T4",     'week':5,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':"Sequence 6",'lesson':"Lesson 5",     'focus':"prefixes",     'explanation':"Pupils apply knowledge of all six prefixes (re-, sub-, super-, inter-, anti-, auto-) by selecting the correct prefix for each root word and using the completed words accurately in sentences.",     'hlWords':["superpower", "recreate", "antifreeze", "anticlockwise", "autograph", "subheading", "interlink", "superman", "subtitle", "reappear"]},
    {'id':"y4-t4-w5-l3",'year':"Y4",'term':"T4",     'week':5,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':"Sequence 6",'lesson':"Lesson 6",     'focus':"prefixes",     'explanation':"Pupils select the correct prefixed word to complete sentences, consolidating understanding of all six prefixes (re-, sub-, super-, inter-, anti-, auto-) and their distinct meanings.",     'hlWords':["subheading", "internet", "antisocial", "superstore", "submerge", "recreate", "autograph", "antifreeze", "superpower", "reappear"]},
    {'id':"y4-t5-w1-l1",'year':"Y4",'term':"T5",     'week':1,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':"Sequence 7",'lesson':"Lesson 1",     'focus':"possessive apostrophes",     'explanation':"An apostrophe is placed before the -s to show that one person or thing owns something (singular possession), e.g. the teacher's book; no apostrophe is needed when -s simply makes a noun plural, e.g. the books.",     'hlWords':["teacher's", "cat's", "boy's", "girl's", "chef's", "flower's", "author's", "friend's", "dog's", "child's"]},
    {'id':"y4-t5-w1-l2",'year':"Y4",'term':"T5",     'week':1,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':"Sequence 7",'lesson':"Lesson 2",     'focus':"possessive apostrophes",     'explanation':"When there is one owner, the apostrophe goes before the -s (singular: builder's tools); when there are multiple owners and the plural already ends in -s, the apostrophe goes after the -s (plural: teachers' offices).",     'hlWords':["builder's", "teachers'", "farmers'", "students'", "boys'", "teacher's", "girl's", "player's", "players'", "coach's"]},
    {'id':"y4-t5-w1-l3",'year':"Y4",'term':"T5",     'week':1,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':"Sequence 7",'lesson':"Lesson 3",     'focus':"possessive apostrophes",     'explanation':"Pupils distinguish between singular possession (apostrophe before -s, e.g. teacher's) and plural possession (apostrophe after -s, e.g. clowns') and apply both rules correctly in a range of sentences.",     'hlWords':["clowns'", "teacher's", "parents'", "coach's", "players'", "musicians'", "musician's", "dog's", "player's", "parent's"]},
    {'id':"y4-t5-w2-l1",'year':"Y4",'term':"T5",     'week':2,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':"Sequence 7",'lesson':"Lesson 4",     'focus':"possessive apostrophes",     'explanation':"Pupils identify whether the owner noun is singular or plural (regular -s plural) and place the apostrophe accordingly — before or after the -s — across a wide range of nouns used in context.",     'hlWords':["dancers'", "explorers'", "turtles'", "shops'", "panda's", "dancer's", "explorer's", "shop's", "turtle's", "farmer's"]},
    {'id':"y4-t5-w2-l2",'year':"Y4",'term':"T5",     'week':2,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':"Sequence 7",'lesson':"Lesson 5",     'focus':"possessive apostrophes",     'explanation':"Irregular plural nouns such as children, women, people and men do not end in -s, so to show possession an apostrophe + s is added directly to the plural form: children's, women's, people's, men's.",     'hlWords':["children's", "women's", "people's", "men's", "mice's", "geese's", "sheep's", "deer's", "oxen's", "teeth's"]},
    {'id':"y4-t5-w2-l3",'year':"Y4",'term':"T5",     'week':2,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':"Sequence 7",'lesson':"Lesson 6",     'focus':"possessive apostrophes",     'explanation':"Pupils apply all three possessive apostrophe rules — singular noun ('s), regular plural noun (s'), irregular plural noun ('s) — identifying and placing the apostrophe correctly across a range of sentence types.",     'hlWords':["men's", "tree's", "phones'", "dog's", "players'", "people's", "women's", "teacher's", "students'", "builder's"]},
    {'id':"y4-t5-w3-l1",'year':"Y4",'term':"T5",     'week':3,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':"Sequence 7",'lesson':"Lesson 7",     'focus':"possessive apostrophes",     'explanation':"Consolidation: pupils decide whether a noun is singular, a regular plural, or an irregular plural, then place the possessive apostrophe before or after the -s accordingly, using a range of common and irregular nouns.",     'hlWords':["mice's", "brother's", "cars'", "workers'", "geese's", "horses'", "people's", "teacher's", "lion's", "lions'"]},
    {'id':"y4-t5-w3-l2",'year':"Y4",'term':"T5",     'week':3,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':"Sequence 7",'lesson':"Lesson 8",     'focus':"possessive apostrophes",     'explanation':"Pupils construct possessive noun phrases by identifying the owner noun, deciding whether it is singular or plural, and building the correct possessive form — for example, choosing between lion's (one lion) and lions' (many lions).",     'hlWords':["lion's", "lions'", "picture's", "pictures'", "children's", "clouds'", "passengers'", "boy's", "boys'", "teacher's"]},
    {'id':"y4-t5-w3-l3",'year':"Y4",'term':"T5",     'week':3,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':"Sequence 7",'lesson':"Lesson 9",     'focus':"possessive apostrophes",     'explanation':"Pupils complete sentences by selecting the correct possessive form, applying all three possessive apostrophe rules to singular, regular plural, and irregular plural nouns including mice, astronauts, pigs, giraffes and shirts.",     'hlWords':["giraffe's", "giraffes'", "shirt's", "shirts'", "mice's", "astronauts'", "pigs'", "children's", "passengers'", "clouds'"]},
    {'id':"y4-t5-w4-l1",'year':"Y4",'term':"T5",     'week':4,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':"Sequence 8",'lesson':"Lesson 1",     'focus':"the -ation suffix",     'explanation':"The suffix -ation turns a verb into a noun; when the verb ends in a consonant, simply add -ation with no change to the root spelling — for example, form → formation, plant → plantation, consider → consideration.",     'hlWords':["foundation", "formation", "relaxation", "plantation", "alteration", "confrontation", "consideration", "information", "expectation", "affirmation"]},
    {'id':"y4-t5-w4-l2",'year':"Y4",'term':"T5",     'week':4,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':"Sequence 8",'lesson':"Lesson 2",     'focus':"the -ation suffix",     'explanation':"When a verb ends in a silent -e, drop the -e before adding -ation to form a noun — for example, prepare → preparation, observe → observation, invite → invitation, combine → combination.",     'hlWords':["valuation", "preparation", "reservation", "adoration", "sensation", "admiration", "invitation", "combination", "observation", "quotation"]},
    {'id':"y4-t5-w4-l3",'year':"Y4",'term':"T5",     'week':4,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':"Sequence 8",'lesson':"Lesson 3",     'focus':"the -ation suffix",     'explanation':"Pupils apply both -ation rules — add directly after consonant-ending roots (e.g. found → foundation) or drop the final -e (e.g. imagine → imagination) — and use words including motivation, declaration and presentation in context.",     'hlWords':["imagination", "presentation", "admiration", "motivation", "declaration", "sensation", "temptation", "consultation", "examination", "starvation"]},
    {'id':"y4-t5-w5-l1",'year':"Y4",'term':"T5",     'week':5,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':"Sequence 9",'lesson':"Lesson 1",     'focus':"uh spelled ou",     'explanation':"The /ʌ/ ('uh') sound is sometimes spelled ou in common words; this does not follow a clear rule and must be learned, though ou frequently appears after the letter c (e.g. country, cousin, courage, couple) or before -ble (e.g. double, trouble).",     'hlWords':["young", "touch", "double", "cousin", "couple", "country", "trouble", "courage", "nourish", "flourish"]},
    {'id':"y4-t5-w5-l2",'year':"Y4",'term':"T5",     'week':5,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':"Sequence 9",'lesson':"Lesson 2",     'focus':"uh spelled ou",     'explanation':"Pupils listen to and spell words where the /ʌ/ sound is spelled ou; many of these words follow the pattern of ou appearing after c (country, cousin, courage, couple) or before -ble/-ple (double, trouble, couple), helping pupils notice and remember the pattern.",     'hlWords':["double", "young", "touch", "couple", "cousin", "nourish", "country", "trouble", "courage", "flourish"]},
    {'id':"y4-t5-w5-l3",'year':"Y4",'term':"T5",     'week':5,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':"Sequence 9",'lesson':"Lesson 3",     'focus':"uh spelled ou",     'explanation':"Pupils identify and correct misspellings of common words where the /ʌ/ sound is spelled ou (e.g. trouble, nourish, flourish, country), consolidating whole-word spellings of this irregular but frequent pattern.",     'hlWords':["trouble", "young", "couple", "double", "nourish", "country", "courage", "cousin", "touch", "flourish"]},
    {'id':"y4-t6-w1-l1",'year':"Y4",'term':"T6",     'week':1,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':"Sequence 10",'lesson':"Lesson 1",     'focus':"Greek & French Sounds",     'explanation':"Three alternative spellings are introduced: 'ch' for the /k/ sound (Greek origin, often in science and music words), 'ch' for the /sh/ sound (French origin), and 'sc' for the /s/ sound (Greek/Latin origin, usually before e, i or y). There are no rules — these words must be learned.",     'hlWords':["architect", "chandelier", "descend", "scientist", "stomach", "parachute", "machine", "monarch", "technology", "character"]},
    {'id':"y4-t6-w1-l2",'year':"Y4",'term':"T6",     'week':1,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':"Sequence 10",'lesson':"Lesson 2",     'focus':"Greek & French Sounds",     'explanation':"Pupils continue practising the three alternative graphemes: 'ch' for /k/ (Greek, e.g. chorus), 'ch' for /sh/ (French, e.g. machine), and 'sc' for /s/ (Greek/Latin, e.g. ascend). Words must be learned individually as there is no predictable rule for when each grapheme appears.",     'hlWords':["isosceles", "orchid", "parachute", "monarch", "machine", "ascend", "architect", "character", "chorus", "chemistry"]},
    {'id':"y4-t6-w1-l3",'year':"Y4",'term':"T6",     'week':1,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':"Sequence 10",'lesson':"Lesson 3",     'focus':"Greek & French Sounds",     'explanation':"Pupils consolidate the three Greek and French graphemes — 'ch' for /k/ (e.g. mechanic), 'ch' for /sh/ (e.g. chalet, brochure), and 'sc' for /s/ (e.g. descend, fascinate) — by identifying and correcting misspellings and applying them in sentence contexts.",     'hlWords':["fascinate", "chalet", "architecture", "descend", "brochure", "character", "mechanic", "scientist", "machine", "stomach"]},
    {'id':"y4-t6-w2-l1",'year':"Y4",'term':"T6",     'week':2,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':"Mastery 3",'lesson':"Lesson 1",     'focus':"prefixes",     'explanation':"Six prefixes are introduced — re- (again/back), sub- (under), super- (above/beyond), inter- (between), anti- (against), and auto- (self) — each added to a root word with no spelling change to the root, creating new words with distinct meanings.",     'hlWords':["reappear", "subheading", "supermarket", "interconnect", "antivirus", "autopilot", "redecorate", "submarine", "superglue", "autobiography"]},
    {'id':"y4-t6-w2-l2",'year':"Y4",'term':"T6",     'week':2,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':"Mastery 3",'lesson':"Lesson 2",     'focus':"prefixes",     'explanation':"Pupils practise selecting the correct prefix from re-, sub-, super-, inter-, anti- and auto- to build new words, understanding that each prefix carries a fixed meaning and attaches to the root word without alteration.",     'hlWords':["antisocial", "supermarket", "submarine", "antigravity", "superglue", "international", "reappear", "autobiography", "subheading", "interconnect"]},
    {'id':"y4-t6-w2-l3",'year':"Y4",'term':"T6",     'week':2,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':"Mastery 3",'lesson':"Lesson 3",     'focus':"prefixes",     'explanation':"Pupils apply understanding of re-, sub-, super-, inter-, anti- and auto- to complete and generate new words, including recognising that one prefix (inter-) can be added to multiple root words such as view, national and net.",     'hlWords':["anticlockwise", "autograph", "recharge", "reconsider", "reconstruct", "subheading", "supermarket", "submarine", "antisocial", "intercity"]},
    {'id':"y4-t6-w3-l1",'year':"Y4",'term':"T6",     'week':3,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':"Mastery 4",'lesson':"Lesson 1",     'focus':"plural apostrophes",     'explanation':"Pupils learn to distinguish singular possession (apostrophe before the 's', e.g. teacher's) from plural possession (apostrophe after the 's', e.g. teachers'). The key question is whether the 'owner' is one person or more than one.",     'hlWords':["teacher's", "teachers'", "player's", "players'", "girl's", "girls'", "driver's", "neighbour's", "neighbours'", "animal's"]},
    {'id':"y4-t6-w3-l2",'year':"Y4",'term':"T6",     'week':3,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':"Mastery 4",'lesson':"Lesson 2",     'focus':"plural apostrophes",     'explanation':"Pupils practise placing the apostrophe correctly by first deciding whether the noun is singular or plural: apostrophe before 's' for one owner (e.g. person's), apostrophe after 's' for multiple owners (e.g. singers'), including irregular plurals like people's.",     'hlWords':["dog's", "dogs'", "house's", "houses'", "people's", "singer's", "singers'", "book's", "books'", "sister's"]},
    {'id':"y4-t6-w3-l3",'year':"Y4",'term':"T6",     'week':3,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':"Mastery 4",'lesson':"Lesson 3",     'focus':"plural apostrophes",     'explanation':"Pupils consolidate singular and plural possessive apostrophes, including irregular plurals such as men's where the plural does not end in 's', requiring the apostrophe before the added 's' despite referring to multiple owners.",     'hlWords':["astronaut's", "astronauts'", "firefighter's", "firefighters'", "student's", "students'", "man's", "men's", "teacher's", "teachers'"]},
    {'id':"y4-t6-w4-l1",'year':"Y4",'term':"T6",     'week':4,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':"Mastery 5",'lesson':"Lesson 1",     'focus':"the -ation suffix",     'explanation':"The suffix -ation turns verbs into nouns. When the root word ends in a consonant, -ation is added directly (e.g. plant → plantation). When the root word ends in 'e', the 'e' must be removed before adding -ation (e.g. inspire → inspiration).",     'hlWords':["plantation", "quotation", "expiration", "affirmation", "invitation", "presentation", "combination", "inspiration", "adaptation", "information"]},
    {'id':"y4-t6-w4-l2",'year':"Y4",'term':"T6",     'week':4,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':"Mastery 5",'lesson':"Lesson 2",     'focus':"the -ation suffix",     'explanation':"Pupils continue applying the -ation suffix to form nouns from verbs, reinforcing the 'drop the e' rule for root words ending in 'e' (e.g. reserve → reservation, combine → combination) alongside straightforward additions (e.g. tempt → temptation).",     'hlWords':["reservation", "temptation", "combination", "confrontation", "information", "expiration", "observation", "invitation", "preparation", "adaptation"]},
    {'id':"y4-t6-w4-l3",'year':"Y4",'term':"T6",     'week':4,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':"Mastery 5",'lesson':"Lesson 3",     'focus':"the -ation suffix",     'explanation':"Pupils consolidate the -ation suffix, applying both the direct addition rule (e.g. install → installation, consult → consultation) and the 'drop the e' rule (e.g. restore → restoration, adapt → adaptation) to generate nouns from given verbs.",     'hlWords':["installation", "consultation", "restoration", "continuation", "confrontation", "expectation", "conservation", "adaptation", "invitation", "information"]},
    {'id':"y4-t6-w5-l1",'year':"Y4",'term':"T6",     'week':5,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':"Mastery 6",'lesson':"Lesson 1",     'focus':"words ending gue/que",     'explanation':"These French-origin spellings represent two sounds: 'gue' at the end of a word makes the /g/ sound (e.g. league, fatigue), while 'que' makes the /k/ sound (e.g. unique, technique). Both graphemes are silent letters added to stabilise the preceding vowel or consonant.",     'hlWords':["league", "plaque", "plague", "mosque", "vague", "unique", "dialogue", "technique", "fatigue", "antique"]},
    {'id':"y4-t6-w5-l2",'year':"Y4",'term':"T6",     'week':5,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':"Mastery 6",'lesson':"Lesson 2",     'focus':"words ending gue/que",     'explanation':"Pupils broaden their repertoire of gue/que words of French origin, sorting a wider range including less common words such as grotesque, synagogue and meringue (gue = /g/) alongside cheque, boutique and physique (que = /k/).",     'hlWords':["grotesque", "synagogue", "meringue", "cheque", "rogue", "tongue", "colleague", "catalogue", "intrigue", "boutique"]},
    {'id':"y4-t6-w5-l3",'year':"Y4",'term':"T6",     'week':5,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':"Mastery 6",'lesson':"Lesson 3",     'focus':"words ending gue/que",     'explanation':"Pupils consolidate gue and que spellings by identifying the final sound (/g/ or /k/) to choose the correct grapheme, noting that technique (French: 'branch of knowledge') and unique require que while monologue, fatigue and colleague require gue.",     'hlWords':["technique", "monologue", "unique", "catalogue", "mosque", "fatigue", "intrigue", "cheque", "colleague", "critique"]},
    {'id':"y5-t1-w1-l1",'year':"Y5",'term':"T1",     'week':1,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':"Revisit",'lesson':"Lesson 1",     'focus':"prefixes",     'explanation':"The prefixes un- (not/reverse), dis- (not/opposite) and mis- (wrongly/badly) are revisited. All attach to the root word without any spelling change. Pupils select the correct prefix by considering which meaning fits the context.",     'hlWords':["unhealthy", "disrespect", "misbehave", "mismatch", "disable", "unknown", "disorder", "misprint", "unwanted", "dishonest"]},
    {'id':"y5-t1-w1-l2",'year':"Y5",'term':"T1",     'week':1,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':"Revisit",'lesson':"Lesson 2",     'focus':"prefixes",     'explanation':"The 'not' prefixes in-, il-, im- and ir- all share the same meaning but the choice depends on the first letter of the root: il- before 'l' (illegal), ir- before 'r' (irrational), im- before 'm' or 'p' (immobile, imperfect), and in- elsewhere.",     'hlWords':["infrequent", "illiterate", "impersonal", "irrational", "incomplete", "immobile", "illogical", "imperfect", "insensitive", "impolite"]},
    {'id':"y5-t1-w1-l3",'year':"Y5",'term':"T1",     'week':1,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':"Revisit",'lesson':"Lesson 3",     'focus':"prefixes",     'explanation':"Pupils revisit the prefixes re- (again), sub- (under), inter- (between), super- (above), anti- (against) and auto- (self), each added to a root word with no spelling change, and practise selecting the correct prefix for a range of root words.",     'hlWords':["autograph", "internet", "antisocial", "submarine", "rebuild", "supernatural", "autocorrect", "supervise", "reconsider", "autobiography"]},
    {'id':"y5-t1-w2-l1",'year':"Y5",'term':"T1",     'week':2,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':"Revisit",'lesson':"Lesson 4",     'focus':"words ending in -sure/-ture",     'explanation':"When a word ends in the /ʒə/ sound (as in 'treasure'), it is spelled -sure. When it ends in the /tʃə/ sound (as in 'picture'), it is spelled -ture. The -ture ending is much more common and often follows a long vowel sound (e.g. creature).",     'hlWords':["treasure", "fracture", "vulture", "capture", "composure", "structure", "adventure", "enclosure", "measure", "creature"]},
    {'id':"y5-t1-w2-l2",'year':"Y5",'term':"T1",     'week':2,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':"Revisit",'lesson':"Lesson 5",     'focus':"the 'uh' sound spelt 'ou'",     'explanation':"In a small group of words from French and Middle English, the short /ʌ/ ('uh') sound is spelled 'ou' rather than 'u' (e.g. touch, double, country). There is no rule — pupils must learn these exception words by heart.",     'hlWords':["touch", "young", "cousin", "double", "trouble", "couple", "country", "courage", "rough", "tough"]},
    {'id':"y5-t1-w2-l3",'year':"Y5",'term':"T1",     'week':2,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':"Revisit",'lesson':"Lesson 6",     'focus':"alternative spellings for k, sh and s",     'explanation':"In words from Greek, 'ch' spells the /k/ sound (school, chorus, stomach); in French-origin words, 'ch' spells /sh/ (chef, machine, brochure); in Latin-origin words, 'sc' spells /s/, usually before 'i' or 'e' (science, scissors, scent).",     'hlWords':["school", "chorus", "stomach", "character", "chef", "machine", "parachute", "science", "scissors", "scent"]},
    {'id':"y5-t1-w3-l1",'year':"Y5",'term':"T1",     'week':3,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':"Revisit",'lesson':"Lesson 7",     'focus':"apostrophes for plural possession",     'explanation':"When more than one owner shares something, the apostrophe is placed after the plural 's' to show possession (e.g. the girls' dresses, the boys' bikes); this differs from singular possession, where the apostrophe comes before the 's' (e.g. my friend's bag).",     'hlWords':["teachers'", "boys'", "dogs'", "players'", "fans'", "girls'", "coaches'", "sisters'", "parents'", "friends'"]},
    {'id':"y5-t1-w3-l2",'year':"Y5",'term':"T1",     'week':3,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':"Revisit",'lesson':"Lesson 8",     'focus':"apostrophes for plural possession",     'explanation':"When a plural form does not end in 's' (such as men, children, women), the apostrophe for possession comes before an added 's' (e.g. the children's drawings, the men's jackets); for regular plurals already ending in 's', the apostrophe simply follows the 's'.",     'hlWords':["men's", "children's", "women's", "people's", "trees'", "teachers'", "students'", "leaves'", "parents'", "boys'"]},
    {'id':"y5-t1-w3-l3",'year':"Y5",'term':"T1",     'week':3,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':"Revisit",'lesson':"Lesson 9",     'focus':"words ending in -gue/-que",     'explanation':"The French ending '-gue' spells the hard /g/ sound at the end of a word (e.g. league, tongue, fatigue), while '-que' spells the hard /k/ sound (e.g. unique, technique, antique); both endings contain a silent 'ue' inherited from French spelling.",     'hlWords':["tongue", "unique", "mosque", "technique", "fatigue", "vague", "antique", "league", "dialogue", "opaque"]},
    {'id':"y5-t1-w4-l1",'year':"Y5",'term':"T1",     'week':4,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':"Sequence 1",'lesson':"Lesson 1",     'focus':"words ending in -cious/-tious",     'explanation':"The suffix '-cious' sounds like 'shus' and is added when the root word ends in 'ce' (drop 'ce', add '-cious', e.g. grace → gracious, malice → malicious) or when a related word ends in '-city' (e.g. ferocity → ferocious, tenacity → tenacious).",     'hlWords':["gracious", "spacious", "malicious", "vicious", "ferocious", "tenacious", "audacious", "capacious", "atrocious", "conscious"]},
    {'id':"y5-t1-w4-l2",'year':"Y5",'term':"T1",     'week':4,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':"Sequence 1",'lesson':"Lesson 2",     'focus':"words ending in -cious/-tious",     'explanation':"The suffix '-tious' sounds like 'shus' and is used when there is a related word ending in '-tion' (e.g. ambition → ambitious, nutrition → nutritious, caution → cautious, repetition → repetitious, infection → infectious).",     'hlWords':["ambitious", "cautious", "nutritious", "infectious", "repetitious", "superstitious", "conscientious", "contentious", "pretentious", "flirtatious"]},
    {'id':"y5-t1-w4-l3",'year':"Y5",'term':"T1",     'week':4,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':"Sequence 1",'lesson':"Lesson 3",     'focus':"words ending in -cious/-tious",     'explanation':"Both '-cious' and '-tious' sound like 'shus'; use '-cious' when the root ends in 'ce' or a related word ends in '-city', and '-tious' when a related word ends in '-tion' (e.g. pretention → pretentious, superstition → superstitious, ambition → ambitious).",     'hlWords':["malicious", "nutritious", "audacious", "pretentious", "ambitious", "gracious", "superstitious", "spacious", "cautious", "repetitious"]},
    {'id':"y5-t1-w5-l1",'year':"Y5",'term':"T1",     'week':5,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':"Sequence 1",'lesson':"Lesson 4",     'focus':"words ending in -cious/-tious",     'explanation':"Applying both rules together: '-cious' follows 'ce' roots or '-city' relatives (e.g. grace → gracious, ferocity → ferocious), and '-tious' follows '-tion' relatives (e.g. caution → cautious, contention → contentious, fraction → fractious).",     'hlWords':["gracious", "cautious", "nutritious", "audacious", "contentious", "spacious", "ferocious", "ambitious", "repetitious", "fractious"]},
    {'id':"y5-t1-w5-l2",'year':"Y5",'term':"T1",     'week':5,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':"Sequence 1",'lesson':"Lesson 5",     'focus':"words ending in -cious/-tious",     'explanation':"Use '-tious' when a related '-tion' word exists (e.g. superstition → superstitious, expedition → expeditious) and '-cious' when the root ends in 'ce' or has a '-city' relative (e.g. office → officious, vice → vicious); both suffixes sound like 'shus'.",     'hlWords':["officious", "superstitious", "ferocious", "repetitious", "vicious", "expeditious", "spacious", "nutritious", "cautious", "malicious"]},
    {'id':"y5-t1-w5-l3",'year':"Y5",'term':"T1",     'week':5,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':"Sequence 1",'lesson':"Lesson 6",     'focus':"words ending in -cious/-tious",     'explanation':"The '-cious' and '-tious' adjective suffixes can carry further prefixes (over-, un-) and suffixes (-ly, -ness) to build longer words (e.g. overcautious, viciously, cautiousness, unambitiously); the same root rules continue to govern which suffix is correct.",     'hlWords':["viciously", "maliciously", "ferociously", "cautiously", "ambitiously", "overcautious", "overambitious", "cautiousness", "ambitiousness", "unambitiously"]},
    {'id':"y5-t2-w1-l1",'year':"Y5",'term':"T2",     'week':1,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':"Sequence 2",'lesson':"Lesson 1",     'focus':"words ending in -cial/-tial",     'explanation':"The suffix '-cial' is usually added after a vowel letter (e.g. official, crucial, special, facial), while '-tial' is usually added after a consonant letter (e.g. essential, martial, potential, torrential, impartial); checking the preceding letter guides the choice.",     'hlWords':["official", "crucial", "special", "beneficial", "martial", "potential", "facial", "essential", "impartial", "torrential"]},
    {'id':"y5-t2-w1-l2",'year':"Y5",'term':"T2",     'week':1,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':"Sequence 2",'lesson':"Lesson 2",     'focus':"words ending in -cial/-tial",     'explanation':"The letter immediately before the suffix determines the spelling: a vowel letter takes '-cial' (e.g. racial, beneficial, official, artificial) while a consonant letter takes '-tial' (e.g. partial, presidential, confidential, celestial, differential).",     'hlWords':["racial", "beneficial", "official", "partial", "presidential", "confidential", "celestial", "martial", "artificial", "impartial"]},
    {'id':"y5-t2-w1-l3",'year':"Y5",'term':"T2",     'week':1,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':"Sequence 2",'lesson':"Lesson 3",     'focus':"words ending in -cial/-tial",     'explanation':"'-cial' follows a vowel letter (e.g. judicial, superficial, artificial, official) and '-tial' follows a consonant letter (e.g. confidential, torrential, sequential, influential, residential); identifying the letter directly before the suffix helps select the correct ending.",     'hlWords':["judicial", "superficial", "artificial", "official", "confidential", "torrential", "sequential", "influential", "residential", "essential"]},
    {'id':"y5-t2-w2-l1",'year':"Y5",'term':"T2",     'week':2,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':"Sequence 2",'lesson':"Lesson 4",     'focus':"words ending in -cial/-tial",     'explanation':"Several common words are exceptions to the vowel/consonant rule: 'financial', 'commercial', 'provincial' and 'palatial' use '-cial' after a consonant, and 'initial' uses '-tial' after a vowel; these exceptions must be learned alongside the main rule.",     'hlWords':["financial", "commercial", "provincial", "initial", "palatial", "official", "essential", "partial", "potential", "special"]},
    {'id':"y5-t2-w2-l2",'year':"Y5",'term':"T2",     'week':2,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':"Sequence 2",'lesson':"Lesson 5",     'focus':"words ending in -cial/-tial",     'explanation':"The vowel/consonant rule continues with a wider vocabulary: a vowel before '-cial' (e.g. official, beneficial, influential) and a consonant before '-tial' (e.g. substantial, consequential); this lesson consolidates the rule using less common but important words.",     'hlWords':["beneficial", "consequential", "substantial", "official", "influential", "special", "essential", "partial", "confidential", "commercial"]},
    {'id':"y5-t2-w2-l3",'year':"Y5",'term':"T2",     'week':2,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':"Sequence 2",'lesson':"Lesson 6",     'focus':"words ending in -cial/-tial",     'explanation':"The '-cial'/'-tial' vowel/consonant rule also applies within longer words carrying prefixes such as anti-, im-, and in-, producing words like antisocial, impartial, and inconsequential; the handful of exceptions (financial, commercial, provincial) must still be learned individually.",     'hlWords':["confidential", "impartial", "antisocial", "inconsequential", "special", "official", "essential", "beneficial", "torrential", "influential"]},
    {'id':"y5-t2-w3-l1",'year':"Y5",'term':"T2",     'week':3,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':"Sequence 3",'lesson':"Lesson 1",     'focus':"doubling consonants",     'explanation':"In multi-syllable words where stress falls on the first syllable (e.g. 'HAP-pen', 'O-pen', 'LIS-ten'), the final consonant is NOT doubled before a vowel suffix, producing words like happening, opening, visited, listened, gardening, and gardener.",     'hlWords':["happening", "entered", "opening", "visited", "limited", "listened", "entering", "gardening", "following", "gardener"]},
    {'id':"y5-t2-w3-l2",'year':"Y5",'term':"T2",     'week':3,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':"Sequence 3",'lesson':"Lesson 2",     'focus':"doubling consonants",     'explanation':"In multi-syllable words ending in a short vowel + consonant where stress falls on the final syllable (e.g. per-MIT, be-GIN, oc-CUR), the final consonant IS doubled before a vowel suffix, producing words like permitted, beginning, occurring, and committed.",     'hlWords':["permitted", "occurring", "controller", "admitted", "controlled", "permitting", "recurring", "committing", "beginning", "regretted"]},
    {'id':"y5-t2-w3-l3",'year':"Y5",'term':"T2",     'week':3,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':"Sequence 3",'lesson':"Lesson 3",     'focus':"doubling consonants",     'explanation':"When adding a vowel suffix, double the final consonant only if stress falls on the last syllable (e.g. control → controlled, occur → occurred, admit → admitted); if stress falls on an earlier syllable, do not double (e.g. limit → limiting, garden → gardener).",     'hlWords':["limiting", "controlled", "propeller", "admitted", "regretted", "beginner", "occurred", "controlling", "limited", "gardener"]},
    {'id':"y5-t2-w4-l1",'year':"Y5",'term':"T2",     'week':4,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':"Sequence 3",'lesson':"Lesson 4",     'focus':"words ending 'fer'",     'explanation':"Words ending in '-fer' double the 'r' before a vowel suffix when the '-fer' syllable remains stressed (e.g. refer → referred/referring, prefer → preferred/preferring), but do not double when stress shifts away from '-fer' (e.g. refer → reference, prefer → preference, suffer → suffering).",     'hlWords':["referred", "referring", "preferred", "preferring", "inferred", "reference", "preference", "suffering", "offered", "referee"]},
    {'id':"y5-t2-w4-l2",'year':"Y5",'term':"T2",     'week':4,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':"Sequence 3",'lesson':"Lesson 5",     'focus':"words ending 'fer'",     'explanation':"When the -fer syllable is stressed, double the r before a vowel suffix (refer→referred, prefer→preferred, transfer→transferred); when the first syllable carries the stress, as in offer or differ, the r is not doubled.",     'hlWords':["referred", "referring", "referral", "transferred", "preferring", "inferred", "conferred", "deferring", "preferred", "transferring"]},
    {'id':"y5-t2-w4-l3",'year':"Y5",'term':"T2",     'week':4,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':"Sequence 3",'lesson':"Lesson 6",     'focus':"words ending 'fer'",     'explanation':"Words ending -fer double the r before vowel suffixes only when the -fer syllable is stressed (inferred, deferring, transferred); the r is not doubled before consonant suffixes such as -ence (inference, difference, preference, conference).",     'hlWords':["inferred", "referring", "offering", "conference", "preference", "differed", "referral", "suffered", "deferred", "inferring"]},
    {'id':"y5-t2-w5-l1",'year':"Y5",'term':"T2",     'week':5,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':"Sequence 3",'lesson':"Lesson 7",     'focus':"words ending 'fer'",     'explanation':"Pupils identify and correct misspellings of -fer words, reinforcing that the r doubles before vowel suffixes only when the -fer syllable is stressed (conferring not confering; referral not referal; transferred not transfered).",     'hlWords':["conferring", "referral", "difference", "offering", "transferred", "preference", "referred", "buffering", "preferred", "inferring"]},
    {'id':"y5-t2-w5-l2",'year':"Y5",'term':"T2",     'week':5,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':"Sequence 3",'lesson':"Lesson 8",     'focus':"words ending 'fer'",     'explanation':"When -fer is stressed, the r doubles before vowel suffixes (referred, conferring, transferring); when adding -ence the stress shifts away from the -fer syllable, so the r is not doubled (reference, inference, difference, preference, conference).",     'hlWords':["reference", "inference", "difference", "preference", "conference", "suffered", "referral", "offered", "transferring", "conferred"]},
    {'id':"y5-t2-w5-l3",'year':"Y5",'term':"T2",     'week':5,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':"Sequence 3",'lesson':"Lesson 9",     'focus':"words ending 'fer'",     'explanation':"Consolidation of the -fer doubling rule through dictation: the r doubles before vowel suffixes when -fer is stressed (conferring, inferred, referring) but not when unstressed or before consonant suffixes (difference, conference, preference).",     'hlWords':["conferring", "inferred", "difference", "buffered", "referring", "conference", "preference", "referred", "transferred", "preferring"]},
    {'id':"y5-t3-w1-l1",'year':"Y5",'term':"T3",     'week':1,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':"Sequence 4",'lesson':"Lesson 1",     'focus':"words ending in -cious/-tious",     'explanation':"Both -cious and -tious sound like 'shus'; use -tious when there is a related word ending in -tion (nutrition→nutritious, repetition→repetitious), and -cious when the root ends in -ce or -city (ferocity→ferocious, malice→malicious).",     'hlWords':["ambitious", "malicious", "fractious", "ferocious", "nutritious", "superstitious", "voracious", "repetitious", "atrocious", "suspicious"]},
