    {'id':"y6-t1-w1-l1",'year':"Y6",'term':"T1",     'week':1,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':"Revisit",'lesson':"Lesson 1",     'focus':"words ending in -cious/-tious",     'explanation':"The suffixes -cious and -tious both sound like 'shus' and form adjectives meaning 'full of' or 'having the quality of'; -tious is used when a related word ends in -tion (e.g. nutrition → nutritious), while -cious often follows a vowel or root words ending in -ce (space → spacious).",     'hlWords':["spacious", "ambitious", "infectious", "cautious", "gracious", "vicious", "nutritious", "malicious", "fictitious", "suspicious"]},
    {'id':"y6-t1-w1-l2",'year':"Y6",'term':"T1",     'week':1,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':"Revisit",'lesson':"Lesson 2",     'focus':"words ending in -cial/-tial",     'explanation':"The suffixes -cial and -tial both sound like 'shul'; -cial typically follows a vowel (special, crucial, artificial) while -tial typically follows a consonant (potential, torrential, residential), with financial and commercial as notable exceptions.",     'hlWords':["official", "special", "crucial", "potential", "beneficial", "torrential", "essential", "residential", "impartial", "artificial"]},
    {'id':"y6-t1-w1-l3",'year':"Y6",'term':"T1",     'week':1,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':"Revisit",'lesson':"Lesson 3",     'focus':"adding vowel suffixes to words ending in 'fer'",     'explanation':"When adding a vowel suffix to a word ending in 'fer', double the r only if the 'fer' syllable is stressed in the new word (e.g. preferred, referring, transferred); if stress shifts away from 'fer', do not double (e.g. reference, preferable, conference).",     'hlWords':["preferred", "preferring", "preferable", "reference", "referring", "transferred", "transferring", "inferred", "inference", "conference"]},
    {'id':"y6-t1-w2-l1",'year':"Y6",'term':"T1",     'week':2,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':"Revisit",'lesson':"Lesson 4",     'focus':"words containing silent letters",     'explanation':"Children revisit the main patterns for silent letters: b after m at a word's end (thumb, crumb), k or g before n at the start (knuckle, gnome), w before r at the start (wreckage), t within consonant clusters (bristle, listen), and n after m at the end (solemn, hymn).",     'hlWords':["knuckle", "wreckage", "solemn", "gnarled", "knitting", "bristle", "honeycomb", "climber", "gnome", "hymn"]},
    {'id':"y6-t1-w2-l2",'year':"Y6",'term':"T1",     'week':2,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':"Revisit",'lesson':"Lesson 5",     'focus':"the 'ough' letter string",     'explanation':"The 'ough' quadgraph can represent at least seven different sounds (oa, off, aw, uff, uh, oo, ow) depending on the word, so each word containing 'ough' must be learned individually alongside its meaning and pronunciation.",     'hlWords':["dough", "through", "although", "trough", "drought", "thorough", "thoughtful", "bought", "plough", "enough"]},
    {'id':"y6-t1-w2-l3",'year':"Y6",'term':"T1",     'week':2,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':"Revisit",'lesson':"Lesson 6",     'focus':"words with 'ei' after the letter c",     'explanation':"The traditional rule 'i before e except after c' applies when the vowel makes the long 'ee' sound: after c, spell the long 'ee' as ei (receive, deceive, ceiling); when the long 'ee' follows any other consonant, use ie (believe, retrieve, thief).",     'hlWords':["receive", "perceive", "deceive", "conceive", "receipt", "believe", "relieve", "retrieve", "thief", "ceiling"]},
    {'id':"y6-t1-w3-l1",'year':"Y6",'term':"T1",     'week':3,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':"Sequence 1",'lesson':"Lesson 1",     'focus':"words ending in -ant/-ent",     'explanation':"The suffix -ent is most commonly used after a soft c (innocent, adjacent), a soft g (diligent, negligent, emergent), or the 'qu' grapheme (frequent, eloquent, subsequent), while other endings such as -er and -id also favour -ent.",     'hlWords':["frequent", "eloquent", "subsequent", "innocent", "adjacent", "urgent", "diligent", "negligent", "intelligent", "emergent"]},
    {'id':"y6-t1-w3-l2",'year':"Y6",'term':"T1",     'week':3,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':"Sequence 1",'lesson':"Lesson 2",     'focus':"words ending in -ant/-ent",     'explanation':"Children practise choosing -ant or -ent: words ending in -ate take -ant (hesitant), words ending in -y typically take -ant (observant), while soft-c or soft-g words take -ent (innocent, diligent); both suffixes sound identical so etymology and related words help determine the correct spelling.",     'hlWords':["innocent", "subsequent", "hesitant", "observant", "tolerant", "celebrant", "diligent", "emigrant", "adjacent", "percent"]},
    {'id':"y6-t1-w3-l3",'year':"Y6",'term':"T1",     'week':3,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':"Sequence 1",'lesson':"Lesson 3",     'focus':"words ending in -ant/-ent",     'explanation':"Children consolidate the -ant/-ent rules by practising a wider range of words: -ant follows -ate roots (dominant, occupant, radiant) while -ent follows soft-g roots (negligent, indulgent, detergent), reinforcing the pattern through independent word-building activities.",     'hlWords':["celebrant", "adjacent", "infrequent", "negligent", "variant", "occupant", "radiant", "indulgent", "detergent", "dominant"]},
    {'id':"y6-t1-w4-l1",'year':"Y6",'term':"T1",     'week':4,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':"Sequence 1",'lesson':"Lesson 4",     'focus':"words ending in -ance/-ence",     'explanation':"The noun-forming suffixes -ance and -ence follow the same pattern as -ant and -ent: -ence is used after soft c (innocence, licence), soft g (diligence, indulgence, emergence), and 'qu' (consequence, eloquence), making the related adjective a reliable guide to spelling.",     'hlWords':["innocence", "licence", "diligence", "indulgence", "emergence", "consequence", "eloquence", "tolerance", "variance", "importance"]},
    {'id':"y6-t1-w4-l2",'year':"Y6",'term':"T1",     'week':4,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':"Sequence 1",'lesson':"Lesson 5",     'focus':"words ending in -ancy/-ency",     'explanation':"The suffixes -ancy and -ency form abstract nouns from -ant and -ent adjectives respectively; -ency is used after soft c or soft g roots (decency, complacency, emergency, contingency, frequency), while -ancy follows -ant words (occupancy, vacancy, expectancy).",     'hlWords':["decency", "complacency", "emergency", "contingency", "frequency", "delinquency", "occupancy", "vacancy", "expectancy", "agency"]},
    {'id':"y6-t1-w4-l3",'year':"Y6",'term':"T1",     'week':4,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':"Sequence 1",'lesson':"Lesson 6",     'focus':"words ending in -ant/-ance/-ancy",     'explanation':"Children consolidate the full -ant/-ance/-ancy family, practising the noun (hesitancy, urgency, occupancy), abstract noun (consequence, importance), and adjective (immigrant, dominant) forms together so they can choose the correct suffix for any given context.",     'hlWords':["immigrant", "hesitancy", "urgency", "frequency", "occupancy", "expectancy", "consequence", "vacancy", "emergency", "dominant"]},
    {'id':"y6-t1-w5-l1",'year':"Y6",'term':"T1",     'week':5,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':"Sequence 1",'lesson':"Lesson 7",     'focus':"words ending in -ant/-ance/-ancy",     'explanation':"Children apply the -ant/-ance/-ancy suffixes in context, focusing on less common words such as observant, consultancy, and contingency; they practise moving between adjective and noun forms (observant → observance, contingent → contingency) to deepen understanding of the suffix family.",     'hlWords':["observant", "eloquence", "consultancy", "contingency", "frequency", "vacancy", "urgency", "occupancy", "emergency", "dominant"]},
    {'id':"y6-t1-w5-l2",'year':"Y6",'term':"T1",     'week':5,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':"Sequence 1",'lesson':"Lesson 8",     'focus':"words ending in -ant/-ance/-ancy",     'explanation':"Children practise the -ant/-ance/-ancy suffix family at greater depth, including higher-demand words such as negligence, applicant, and expectancy, and explain in writing which spelling rule applies and why, consolidating understanding across the whole sequence.",     'hlWords':["negligence", "expectancy", "applicant", "occupancy", "compliance", "relevance", "abundance", "significant", "tolerance", "hesitancy"]},
    {'id':"y6-t1-w5-l3",'year':"Y6",'term':"T1",     'week':5,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':"Sequence 1",'lesson':"Lesson 9",     'focus':"words ending in -ant/-ance/-ancy",     'explanation':"In the mastery lesson, children apply the -ant/-ent/-ance/-ence/-ancy/-ency suffix families to complex and prefixed words (overindulgence, unintelligently, predominantly, unfrequented), demonstrating secure understanding by using them accurately in extended sentences.",     'hlWords':["overindulgence", "unintelligently", "predominantly", "unfrequented", "negligence", "expectancy", "applicant", "hesitancy", "consultancy", "observant"]},
    {'id':"y6-t2-w1-l1",'year':"Y6",'term':"T2",     'week':1,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':"Sequence 2",'lesson':"Lesson 1",     'focus':"words ending in -ible/-able",     'explanation':"Use -able when a complete root word can be heard (e.g. accept → acceptable, comfort → comfortable) or when there is a related -ate/-ation word; -ible is used when no recognisable root word remains.",     'hlWords':["suitable", "readable", "adaptable", "treatable", "acceptable", "comfortable", "laughable", "printable", "portable", "reasonable"]},
    {'id':"y6-t2-w1-l2",'year':"Y6",'term':"T2",     'week':1,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':"Sequence 2",'lesson':"Lesson 2",     'focus':"words ending in -ible/-able",     'explanation':"Both -able (used with a recognisable root word) and -ible (used when no complete root remains) create adjectives; pupils compare pairs such as adaptable/possible and readable/audible to identify which suffix applies.",     'hlWords':["suitable", "readable", "adaptable", "acceptable", "treatable", "terrible", "possible", "invisible", "audible", "divisible"]},
    {'id':"y6-t2-w1-l3",'year':"Y6",'term':"T2",     'week':1,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':"Sequence 2",'lesson':"Lesson 3",     'focus':"words ending in -ible/-able",     'explanation':"The adverb suffixes -ibly and -ably are added to -ible and -able adjectives respectively; -ably is more common because -able is more common, and the same root-word rule applies when choosing between them.",     'hlWords':["remarkably", "audibly", "affordably", "horribly", "adaptably", "divisibly", "possibly", "terribly", "suitably", "incredibly"]},
    {'id':"y6-t2-w2-l1",'year':"Y6",'term':"T2",     'week':2,'weekLesson':1,     'sequence':"Sequence 2",'lesson':"Lesson 4",     'focus':"words ending in -ible/-able",     'explanation':"When a related -ate or -ation word exists, use -able: observation → observable, application → applicable, presentation → presentable, consideration → considerable; this -ation pattern is a reliable guide for -able words.",     'hlWords':["observable", "applicable", "presentable", "considerable", "respectable", "readable", "audible", "impossible", "inflatable", "terrible"]},
    {'id':"y6-t2-w2-l2",'year':"Y6",'term':"T2",     'week':2,'weekLesson':2,     'sequence':"Sequence 2",'lesson':"Lesson 5",     'focus':"words ending in -ible/-able",     'explanation':"When a root word ends in a silent -e, drop the e before adding -able: value → valuable, note → notable, desire → desirable, compare → comparable; a common error is retaining the e (e.g. valueable).",     'hlWords':["valuable", "notable", "desirable", "comparable", "removable", "adorable", "considerable", "presentable", "audible", "impossible"]},
    {'id':"y6-t2-w2-l3",'year':"Y6",'term':"T2",     'week':2,'weekLesson':3,     'sequence':"Sequence 2",'lesson':"Lesson 6",     'focus':"words ending in -ible/-able",     'explanation':"When the root word ends in -ce or -ge, the e must be kept before adding -able to preserve the soft sound: change → changeable, manage → manageable, notice → noticeable, knowledge → knowledgeable.",     'hlWords':["changeable", "manageable", "damageable", "knowledgeable", "noticeable", "chargeable", "replaceable", "acceptable", "adorable", "credible"]},
